@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class AdvancedLearningDataService {
  getAdvancedModules(): LearningModule[] {
    return [
      {
        id: 'taor-pattern',
        title: 'Think-Act-Observe-Repeat (TAOR)',
        description: 'The core reasoning loop that makes AI agents accurate and reliable',
        icon: '🔄',
        color: '#0984e3',
        order: 7,
        lessons: [
          {
            id: 'taor-explained',
            moduleId: 'taor-pattern',
            title: 'The TAOR Loop Explained',
            description: 'Deep dive into the reasoning pattern that powers all effective AI agents',
            order: 1,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Think-Act-Observe-Repeat: The Core Agent Pattern\n\nEvery effective AI agent follows the same fundamental cycle. Whether it\'s Claude Code fixing a bug or a multi-agent system deploying code, the underlying pattern is:\n\n### The TAOR Cycle\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                                                 │\n│   1. THINK                                      │\n│   ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐       │\n│   │ • What is the current situation?    │       │\n│   │ • What do I know vs not know?       │       │\n│   │ • What should I do next and WHY?    │       │\n│   │ • What could go wrong?              │       │\n│   └─────────────────────────────────────┘       │\n│                    │                            │\n│                    ▼                            │\n│   2. ACT                                        │\n│   ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐       │\n│   │ • Take ONE specific action          │       │\n│   │ • Use the right tool for the job    │       │\n│   │ • Be precise in what you request    │       │\n│   └─────────────────────────────────────┘       │\n│                    │                            │\n│                    ▼                            │\n│   3. OBSERVE                                    │\n│   ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐       │\n│   │ • What was the actual result?       │       │\n│   │ • Did it match my expectation?      │       │\n│   │ • What new information do I have?   │       │\n│   │ • Did anything unexpected happen?   │       │\n│   └─────────────────────────────────────┘       │\n│                    │                            │\n│                    ▼                            │\n│   4. REPEAT (or STOP)                           │\n│   ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐       │\n│   │ • Is the goal achieved?             │       │\n│   │ • If yes → return result            │       │\n│   │ • If no → back to THINK with        │       │\n│   │   updated understanding             │       │\n│   └─────────────────────────────────────┘       │\n│                                                 │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Why TAOR Produces Accurate Results\n\n1. **Single actions reduce error** — doing one thing at a time means you catch mistakes immediately\n2. **Observation forces grounding** — you verify reality instead of assuming\n3. **Iteration allows course correction** — each loop refines your understanding\n4. **Explicit thinking prevents blind execution** — reasoning before acting catches bad plans' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// The TAOR loop in code — this is how Claude Code works internally\nimport Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";\n\nconst client = new Anthropic();\n\nconst TAOR_SYSTEM_PROMPT = `You are an AI agent that follows the TAOR pattern strictly.\n\nFor EVERY action you take:\n1. THINK: Explain your reasoning. What do you know? What do you need?\n   Write your thoughts in <thinking> tags.\n2. ACT: Take exactly ONE action using the available tools.\n3. OBSERVE: After receiving the result, analyze it carefully.\n4. REPEAT: Decide if you need another cycle or if the task is complete.\n\nNever take multiple actions without observing results between them.\nNever assume — always verify.\nIf something unexpected happens, re-think from scratch.`;\n\nasync function taorAgentLoop(task: string, tools: Anthropic.Tool[]) {\n  const messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] = [\n    { role: "user", content: task }\n  ];\n\n  let iterations = 0;\n  const MAX_ITERATIONS = 30;\n\n  while (iterations < MAX_ITERATIONS) {\n    iterations++;\n\n    // THINK + ACT: Claude reasons and decides on an action\n    const response = await client.messages.create({\n      model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414",\n      max_tokens: 4096,\n      system: TAOR_SYSTEM_PROMPT,\n      tools,\n      messages\n    });\n\n    messages.push({ role: "assistant", content: response.content });\n\n    // REPEAT check: Is the task done?\n    if (response.stop_reason === "end_turn") {\n      return extractFinalAnswer(response);\n    }\n\n    // ACT was a tool call — now we OBSERVE\n    if (response.stop_reason === "tool_use") {\n      const toolUse = response.content.find(b => b.type === "tool_use")!;\n      \n      // Execute the action\n      const result = await executeTool(toolUse.name, toolUse.input);\n      \n      // Feed observation back for the next THINK cycle\n      messages.push({\n        role: "user",\n        content: [{\n          type: "tool_result",\n          tool_use_id: toolUse.id,\n          content: result\n        }]\n      });\n    }\n  }\n\n  return { error: "Max iterations reached" };\n}', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'The key insight: humans naturally follow TAOR when doing complex work. You read code (observe), think about what it does, make a change (act), then test it (observe again). AI agents become accurate when they follow this same disciplined cycle instead of trying to do everything at once.' },
              { type: 'agent-demo', content: 'taor-loop-demo' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'The #1 failure mode of AI agents is skipping the OBSERVE step — acting on assumptions instead of checking results. Always force your agents to verify before proceeding.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'Why does the TAOR pattern take only ONE action per cycle?', options: ['To be slower and more careful', 'So errors are caught immediately before compounding', 'Because LLMs can only call one tool', 'To reduce API costs'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Taking one action at a time means you observe the result immediately. If something goes wrong, you catch it before it cascades into bigger problems.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'What happens in the OBSERVE step?', options: ['The agent takes another action', 'The agent analyzes the actual result and compares it to expectations', 'The agent sends a response to the user', 'The agent resets its context'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'OBSERVE is about grounding — analyzing the actual result, checking if it matches expectations, and identifying any new information or unexpected behavior.' },
              { id: 'q3', question: 'When does the TAOR loop terminate?', options: ['After a fixed number of steps', 'When the agent decides the goal is achieved', 'When all tools have been used', 'After 5 minutes'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'The loop continues until the agent determines the goal is achieved (or a safety limit is hit). The agent explicitly decides whether to loop or stop.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'taor-prompts',
            moduleId: 'taor-pattern',
            title: 'Structuring Agent Prompts for TAOR',
            description: 'How to write system prompts that enforce disciplined reasoning',
            order: 2,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Writing Prompts That Enforce TAOR\n\nThe difference between a chaotic agent and a reliable one is the system prompt. Your prompt must force the model to:\n\n1. **Think before acting** — explicit reasoning step\n2. **Act minimally** — one tool call at a time\n3. **Observe critically** — don\'t just pass through results\n4. **Decide consciously** — explicit done/continue decision\n\n### Bad vs Good Agent Prompts\n\n**BAD prompt** (leads to blind execution):\n```\nYou are a helpful assistant. Complete the user\'s task using the available tools.\n```\n\n**GOOD prompt** (enforces TAOR):\n```\nYou are a senior developer agent. For every task:\n\n1. First, analyze what you know and what you need to find out.\n2. Take ONE action at a time — never chain multiple assumptions.\n3. After each action, verify the result before continuing.\n4. If something is unexpected, stop and re-evaluate your approach.\n5. Only declare done when you\'ve verified the task is complete.\n```' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Production-grade TAOR system prompt\nconst DEVELOPMENT_AGENT_PROMPT = `You are a senior software engineer agent.\n\n## Core Behavior: Think-Act-Observe-Repeat\n\nFor EVERY step in your work:\n\n### THINK (required before every action)\n- State what you currently understand about the task\n- Identify what information you\'re missing\n- Explain WHY you\'re choosing this next action\n- Consider what could go wrong\n\n### ACT (one action only)\n- Take exactly ONE action using available tools\n- Be specific — read specific files, not entire directories\n- Prefer verification over assumption\n\n### OBSERVE (required after every result)\n- Summarize what the result tells you\n- Note anything unexpected\n- Update your mental model of the situation\n\n### REPEAT or COMPLETE\n- If the task is done AND verified: provide final answer\n- If more work needed: return to THINK with updated context\n\n## Rules\n- Never modify code without first reading it\n- Never assume a fix works without testing\n- If a test fails, read the error carefully before retrying\n- If stuck after 3 attempts, try a different approach\n- Always verify your changes compile/pass before declaring done`;\n\n// Using it with Claude\nconst response = await client.messages.create({\n  model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414",\n  max_tokens: 8192,\n  system: DEVELOPMENT_AGENT_PROMPT,\n  tools: [\n    { name: "read_file", description: "Read a file\'s contents", input_schema: { type: "object", properties: { path: { type: "string" } }, required: ["path"] } },\n    { name: "write_file", description: "Write content to a file", input_schema: { type: "object", properties: { path: { type: "string" }, content: { type: "string" } }, required: ["path", "content"] } },\n    { name: "run_command", description: "Run a shell command", input_schema: { type: "object", properties: { command: { type: "string" } }, required: ["command"] } },\n    { name: "search_code", description: "Search codebase for a pattern", input_schema: { type: "object", properties: { pattern: { type: "string" }, path: { type: "string" } }, required: ["pattern"] } }\n  ],\n  messages: [{ role: "user", content: "Fix the authentication bug in the login endpoint" }]\n});', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Prompt Techniques That Enforce Quality\n\n| Technique | What it Does | Example |\n|-----------|-------------|--------|\n| **Mandatory reasoning** | Forces THINK step | "Before any action, explain your reasoning" |\n| **Single-action constraint** | Forces focused ACT | "Take exactly one action at a time" |\n| **Verification requirement** | Forces OBSERVE | "Never assume — always verify results" |\n| **Exit criteria** | Forces explicit REPEAT decision | "Only declare done when tests pass" |\n| **Failure protocols** | Handles edge cases | "If stuck after 3 tries, try a different approach" |' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Pro tip: Use Claude\'s Extended Thinking (thinking mode) to make the THINK step explicit. With `thinking: { type: "enabled", budget_tokens: 10000 }`, Claude will reason extensively before choosing an action — making the TAOR pattern even more powerful.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What makes a "bad" agent prompt?', options: ['Being too long', 'Not enforcing reasoning before action', 'Using complex language', 'Including code examples'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'A bad agent prompt lets the model act without thinking first. Good prompts force explicit reasoning (THINK) before every action.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'Why include "if stuck after 3 attempts, try a different approach" in your prompt?', options: ['To limit API costs', 'To prevent infinite loops of the same failed strategy', 'To make the agent faster', 'It\'s a requirement of the API'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Without this, agents can get stuck retrying the same failed approach. Explicit failure protocols force the agent to adapt — a critical part of the REPEAT step.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'jira-to-taor',
            moduleId: 'taor-pattern',
            title: 'From Jira Ticket to Agent Execution Plan',
            description: 'Decompose any task into a TAOR execution using real-world workflows',
            order: 3,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Turning Jira Tickets into Agent Work\n\nYour team reads Jira tickets every day. The skill is teaching agents to do the same — decompose a ticket into a series of TAOR cycles.\n\n### The Decomposition Process\n\n1. **Read the ticket** → OBSERVE what\'s required\n2. **Analyze requirements** → THINK about what\'s needed\n3. **Plan the approach** → THINK about how to implement\n4. **Execute each step** → ACT one step at a time\n5. **Verify each step** → OBSERVE results\n6. **Validate completion** → Check acceptance criteria\n\n### Example: Jira Ticket PROJ-456\n\n```\nTitle: Add pagination to GET /api/users endpoint\nDescription: The users list endpoint returns all users at once.\n  Add cursor-based pagination with configurable page size.\nAcceptance Criteria:\n- [ ] Supports `cursor` and `limit` query params\n- [ ] Default limit is 20, max is 100\n- [ ] Response includes `next_cursor` for next page\n- [ ] Empty cursor returns first page\n- [ ] Existing clients still work (backward compatible)\n```\n\n### Agent Decomposition:\n\n```\nCycle 1: THINK → I need to understand the current endpoint\n         ACT  → Read the users controller file\n         OBS  → Found GET /users handler at line 45\n\nCycle 2: THINK → I need to understand the data layer\n         ACT  → Read the users service/repository\n         OBS  → Uses Prisma with findMany(), no pagination\n\nCycle 3: THINK → I\'ll add cursor-based pagination to the service\n         ACT  → Modify users.service.ts with cursor logic\n         OBS  → File updated successfully\n\nCycle 4: THINK → Now update the controller to accept params\n         ACT  → Modify users.controller.ts\n         OBS  → Controller now parses cursor & limit\n\nCycle 5: THINK → I should add validation for limit bounds\n         ACT  → Add validation pipe/guard\n         OBS  → Validation added, default 20, max 100\n\nCycle 6: THINK → Need to verify it works\n         ACT  → Run existing tests\n         OBS  → All pass — backward compatible ✓\n\nCycle 7: THINK → Need new tests for pagination\n         ACT  → Write pagination-specific tests\n         OBS  → 5 new tests, all passing ✓\n\nDONE → All acceptance criteria met\n```' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Full implementation: Jira ticket → TAOR agent execution\nimport Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";\n\nconst client = new Anthropic();\n\nconst JIRA_AGENT_PROMPT = `You are a development agent that works from Jira tickets.\n\nWhen given a Jira ticket:\n1. THINK: Parse the requirements and acceptance criteria\n2. THINK: Plan your implementation approach\n3. For each step in your plan:\n   - THINK: What specifically needs to change?\n   - ACT: Make ONE change (read, write, or test)\n   - OBSERVE: Verify the change worked\n4. After all changes: verify ALL acceptance criteria are met\n5. Only declare done when every criterion is checked off\n\nImportant:\n- Read existing code before modifying\n- Maintain backward compatibility unless told otherwise\n- Run tests after changes\n- If a test fails, fix it before moving on`;\n\nasync function executeJiraTicket(ticketId: string) {\n  // Fetch ticket from Jira MCP\n  const ticket = await jiraClient.getIssue(ticketId);\n  \n  const task = `Execute this Jira ticket:\n\nTitle: ${ticket.fields.summary}\nDescription: ${ticket.fields.description}\nAcceptance Criteria:\n${ticket.fields.customfield_acceptance || "See description"}\n\nWork through this systematically using TAOR.\nVerify each acceptance criterion before declaring done.`;\n\n  // Run the TAOR loop\n  const result = await taorAgentLoop(task, developmentTools);\n  \n  // Transition ticket to "In Review"\n  await jiraClient.transitionIssue(ticketId, "In Review");\n  \n  return result;\n}', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'agent-demo', content: 'jira-taor-demo' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Teach your team: before asking Claude to implement a ticket, first write out the TAOR cycles yourself. "What would I observe first? What would I think? What single action would I take?" This mental exercise helps you write better prompts and catch when the agent goes off-track.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'In the Jira-to-TAOR flow, what does the agent do FIRST?', options: ['Start writing code', 'Read the existing implementation', 'Create a branch', 'Run the tests'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'The first TAOR cycle is always OBSERVE — read and understand what currently exists before making any changes.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'debugging-agents',
            moduleId: 'taor-pattern',
            title: 'Debugging Agent Reasoning',
            description: 'When agents go wrong — diagnosing failures in the TAOR loop',
            order: 4,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## When Agents Fail: Diagnosing TAOR Breakdowns\n\nAgents fail in predictable ways. Each failure maps to a specific TAOR step:\n\n### Failure Taxonomy\n\n| Failure Type | Broken Step | Symptom | Fix |\n|-------------|-------------|---------|-----|\n| **Blind execution** | THINK | Agent acts without understanding context | Add "explain your reasoning before acting" |\n| **Wrong tool** | ACT | Agent uses grep when it should read a file | Clarify tool descriptions |\n| **Ignored error** | OBSERVE | Agent proceeds despite failed command | Add "if the result is an error, stop and analyze" |\n| **Infinite loop** | REPEAT | Agent keeps trying same failed approach | Add "after 3 failures, try a different strategy" |\n| **Premature exit** | REPEAT | Agent declares done without verifying | Add "verify all acceptance criteria before finishing" |\n| **Hallucination** | THINK | Agent invents file paths or function names | Add "never assume — always verify existence first" |\n\n### Using Extended Thinking to Debug\n\nClaude\'s Extended Thinking mode shows you the THINK step explicitly. Enable it to see where reasoning goes wrong:' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Enable extended thinking to see agent reasoning\nconst response = await client.messages.create({\n  model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414",\n  max_tokens: 16000,\n  thinking: {\n    type: "enabled",\n    budget_tokens: 10000  // Allow up to 10K tokens of reasoning\n  },\n  system: TAOR_SYSTEM_PROMPT,\n  tools: developmentTools,\n  messages: [{ role: "user", content: task }]\n});\n\n// Extract the thinking blocks to see reasoning\nfor (const block of response.content) {\n  if (block.type === "thinking") {\n    console.log("🧠 AGENT THINKING:", block.thinking);\n    // This reveals:\n    // - What the agent believes is true\n    // - Why it chose a specific action\n    // - What it expects to happen\n    // - Where reasoning might be flawed\n  }\n  if (block.type === "tool_use") {\n    console.log("🔧 ACTION:", block.name, block.input);\n  }\n}\n\n// Common debugging pattern: trace the full conversation\nfunction traceAgentExecution(messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[]) {\n  for (const msg of messages) {\n    if (msg.role === "assistant") {\n      const content = Array.isArray(msg.content) ? msg.content : [msg.content];\n      for (const block of content) {\n        if (typeof block === "object") {\n          if (block.type === "thinking") console.log("💭 THINK:", block.thinking?.slice(0, 200));\n          if (block.type === "tool_use") console.log("⚡ ACT:", block.name);\n          if (block.type === "text") console.log("💬 SAY:", block.text?.slice(0, 100));\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    if (msg.role === "user") {\n      const content = Array.isArray(msg.content) ? msg.content : [msg.content];\n      for (const block of content) {\n        if (typeof block === "object" && block.type === "tool_result") {\n          console.log("👁️ OBSERVE:", String(block.content)?.slice(0, 100));\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'The most dangerous failure: the agent says "Done!" without actually verifying. Always add explicit verification steps to your prompts: "Run tests and confirm they pass" or "Read the file back to confirm changes applied correctly."' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Debugging Checklist\n\nWhen an agent produces wrong results, ask:\n\n1. **Did it THINK correctly?** → Check extended thinking output\n2. **Did it ACT on the right thing?** → Check tool inputs\n3. **Did it OBSERVE accurately?** → Check if it read the tool result correctly\n4. **Did it REPEAT appropriately?** → Did it stop too early or loop too long?\n\nUsually the fix is adding one sentence to your system prompt.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'An agent keeps trying the same fix that doesn\'t work. Which TAOR step is broken?', options: ['THINK', 'ACT', 'OBSERVE', 'REPEAT'], correctIndex: 3, explanation: 'The REPEAT step should evaluate whether the current strategy is working. If the agent doesn\'t adapt after failures, the REPEAT logic is broken — it needs a prompt instruction like "after 3 failures, try a different approach."' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'How does Extended Thinking help debug agents?', options: ['It makes the agent faster', 'It shows the explicit reasoning before each action', 'It reduces API costs', 'It adds more tools'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Extended Thinking shows you what the agent was reasoning about before it chose an action. This reveals flawed assumptions, missed information, or incorrect logic.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'team-agents',
            moduleId: 'taor-pattern',
            title: 'Team Agents: Organizing Multiple TAOR Loops',
            description: 'Coordinate multiple agents each running their own TAOR cycle',
            order: 5,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Multiple Agents, Each with TAOR\n\nWhen you have a team of agents, EACH agent runs its own TAOR loop, but an orchestrator coordinates them:\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│         ORCHESTRATOR (its own TAOR loop)         │\n│                                                 │\n│  THINK: "This task needs planning, coding,      │\n│          and testing. I\'ll delegate."            │\n│                                                 │\n│  ACT: Delegate to Planner Agent                 │\n│  OBSERVE: Plan received ✓                       │\n│                                                 │\n│  ACT: Delegate to Coder Agent                   │\n│  OBSERVE: Code implemented ✓                    │\n│                                                 │\n│  ACT: Delegate to Tester Agent                  │\n│  OBSERVE: Tests failed! ✗                       │\n│                                                 │\n│  THINK: "Tests failed. I need to send the       │\n│          error back to the Coder."              │\n│                                                 │\n│  ACT: Send failure to Coder with test output    │\n│  OBSERVE: Coder fixed the issue ✓              │\n│                                                 │\n│  ACT: Re-run Tester                             │\n│  OBSERVE: All tests pass ✓                     │\n│                                                 │\n│  DONE                                           │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n     ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐\n     │ PLANNER  │  │  CODER   │  │  TESTER  │\n     │          │  │          │  │          │\n     │ T→A→O→R │  │ T→A→O→R │  │ T→A→O→R │\n     │ T→A→O→R │  │ T→A→O→R │  │ T→A→O→R │\n     │ ...done  │  │ T→A→O→R │  │ ...done  │\n     │          │  │ ...done  │  │          │\n     └──────────┘  └──────────┘  └──────────┘\n```\n\n### Key Principle: Each Agent Has a Focused Role\n\nJust like a real dev team, each agent has:\n- A **specific expertise** (planning, coding, testing, reviewing)\n- Its **own TAOR loop** with domain-specific tools\n- A **clear interface** (what it receives, what it outputs)' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Multi-agent TAOR orchestration\nconst ORCHESTRATOR_PROMPT = `You are a tech lead coordinating a development team.\n\nYour team:\n- planner_agent: Analyzes requirements, creates implementation plans\n- coder_agent: Writes and modifies code\n- tester_agent: Writes and runs tests\n- reviewer_agent: Reviews code for quality and security\n\nFor each task:\n1. THINK: What agents do I need and in what order?\n2. ACT: Delegate to ONE agent at a time\n3. OBSERVE: Check the agent\'s output\n4. REPEAT: Continue delegating until all work is done and verified\n\nIf an agent fails or produces poor results:\n- Send specific feedback about what\'s wrong\n- Let them retry with the feedback\n- If still failing after 2 retries, try a different agent or approach`;\n\nconst CODER_PROMPT = `You are a senior developer. You receive coding tasks.\n\nFor each task:\n1. THINK: Read existing code first. Understand the patterns.\n2. ACT: Make focused changes, one file at a time.\n3. OBSERVE: Verify your changes compile and look correct.\n4. REPEAT: Continue until implementation is complete.\n\nRules:\n- Follow existing code style and patterns\n- Never modify test files (that\'s the tester\'s job)\n- If you need clarification, ask rather than assume`;\n\nconst TESTER_PROMPT = `You are a QA engineer. You write and run tests.\n\nFor each task:\n1. THINK: What needs testing? What are the edge cases?\n2. ACT: Write test cases one at a time.\n3. OBSERVE: Run the tests, check results.\n4. REPEAT: Add more tests until coverage is comprehensive.\n\nAlways test:\n- Happy path\n- Edge cases (empty, null, max values)\n- Error conditions\n- Backward compatibility`;\n\n// Orchestrator delegates with TAOR\nasync function orchestrateTeam(task: string) {\n  const agents = {\n    planner: { prompt: PLANNER_PROMPT, tools: [readFile, searchCode] },\n    coder: { prompt: CODER_PROMPT, tools: [readFile, writeFile, runCommand] },\n    tester: { prompt: TESTER_PROMPT, tools: [readFile, writeFile, runCommand] },\n    reviewer: { prompt: REVIEWER_PROMPT, tools: [readFile, searchCode] }\n  };\n\n  // Orchestrator runs its own TAOR loop\n  return await taorAgentLoop(task, [\n    {\n      name: "delegate_to_agent",\n      description: "Delegate a sub-task to a specialist agent",\n      input_schema: {\n        type: "object",\n        properties: {\n          agent: { type: "string", enum: Object.keys(agents) },\n          task: { type: "string", description: "Clear description of what to do" },\n          context: { type: "string", description: "Relevant context from previous steps" }\n        },\n        required: ["agent", "task"]\n      }\n    }\n  ]);\n}', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'agent-demo', content: 'team-agents-demo' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Map your actual team structure to agents: if you have a tech lead, 3 devs, and a QA engineer, create those same roles as agents. The orchestrator is the tech lead, specialist agents are the team members. This makes agent behavior predictable because it mirrors how your team already works.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'In a multi-agent TAOR system, who runs their own TAOR loop?', options: ['Only the orchestrator', 'Only the specialist agents', 'Everyone — orchestrator AND specialists', 'Only the user'], correctIndex: 2, explanation: 'Every agent in the system runs its own TAOR loop. The orchestrator thinks about delegation and observes specialist outputs. Each specialist thinks about their domain and acts with their specific tools.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'What should the orchestrator do when a specialist agent fails?', options: ['Retry immediately', 'Skip that step', 'Send specific feedback and let them retry', 'Replace with a different model'], correctIndex: 2, explanation: 'The orchestrator should OBSERVE the failure, THINK about what went wrong, then ACT by sending specific feedback to the specialist. This is TAOR applied to coordination.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'structured-output',
            moduleId: 'taor-pattern',
            title: 'Structured Output & Reliable Extraction',
            description: 'Using tool_use for guaranteed JSON, validation loops, and parsing agent responses',
            order: 6,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Getting Reliable Structured Data from LLMs\n\nAgents don\'t just generate text — they produce structured decisions: which tool to call, what parameters to pass, what severity to assign. If the output format is unreliable, your entire orchestration breaks.\n\n### The Problem\n\nAsking an LLM for JSON in a free-form response is fragile:\n- The model might add explanatory text before/after the JSON\n- It might use single quotes instead of double quotes\n- It might hallucinate fields or omit required ones\n- Nested structures can get malformed\n\n### Solution 1: Tool Use as Structured Output\n\nThe most reliable approach: define a "tool" whose schema IS your desired output format. The model will call that tool with properly formatted parameters.\n\n```\nInstead of: "Please respond with JSON: {severity, message, fix}"\n\nDo: Define a tool called "report_finding" with those parameters.\nThe model MUST provide valid args to call it → guaranteed schema.\n```\n\nThis works because tool calling is a first-class API feature with schema validation, not a freeform text generation task.\n\n### Solution 2: Prefilled Response\n\nStart the assistant response with `{` to force JSON mode:\n```\nmessages: [\n  { role: "user", content: "Analyze this code..." },\n  { role: "assistant", content: "{" }  // Prefill forces JSON continuation\n]\n```\n\n### Solution 3: Validation Loop (TAOR-Style)\n\n1. **Act**: Generate the output\n2. **Observe**: Parse it with a strict schema (Zod, JSON Schema)\n3. **If invalid → Think**: Send the validation error back to the model\n4. **Repeat**: Model corrects its output\n\nThis self-healing pattern gets valid output 99%+ of the time within 1-2 retries.' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Three approaches to structured output with Claude\nimport Anthropic from \"@anthropic-ai/sdk\";\nimport { z } from \"zod\";\n\nconst client = new Anthropic();\n\n// =============================================\n// APPROACH 1: Tool Use as Structured Output\n// (Most reliable — recommended for production)\n// =============================================\n\nconst findingSchema: Anthropic.Tool = {\n  name: \"report_finding\",\n  description: \"Report a code review finding with structured data\",\n  input_schema: {\n    type: \"object\",\n    properties: {\n      severity: {\n        type: \"string\",\n        enum: [\"critical\", \"high\", \"medium\", \"low\"],\n        description: \"Issue severity level\"\n      },\n      file: { type: \"string\", description: \"File path\" },\n      line: { type: \"number\", description: \"Line number\" },\n      issue: { type: \"string\", description: \"Description of the problem\" },\n      suggestion: { type: \"string\", description: \"How to fix it\" }\n    },\n    required: [\"severity\", \"file\", \"line\", \"issue\", \"suggestion\"]\n  }\n};\n\nasync function getStructuredReview(code: string) {\n  const response = await client.messages.create({\n    model: \"claude-sonnet-4-6-20250514\",\n    max_tokens: 1024,\n    tools: [findingSchema],\n    tool_choice: { type: \"tool\", name: \"report_finding\" }, // FORCE this tool\n    messages: [{ role: \"user\", content: `Review this code:\\n${code}` }]\n  });\n\n  const toolUse = response.content.find(b => b.type === \"tool_use\")!;\n  return toolUse.input; // Guaranteed to match the schema\n}\n\n// =============================================\n// APPROACH 2: Zod Validation Loop\n// (Good for complex schemas with custom rules)\n// =============================================\n\nconst ReviewSchema = z.object({\n  findings: z.array(z.object({\n    severity: z.enum([\"critical\", \"high\", \"medium\", \"low\"]),\n    file: z.string(),\n    line: z.number().int().positive(),\n    issue: z.string().min(10),\n    suggestion: z.string().min(10)\n  })),\n  summary: z.string(),\n  overallRisk: z.enum([\"safe\", \"needs-review\", \"dangerous\"])\n});\n\ntype ReviewResult = z.infer<typeof ReviewSchema>;\n\nasync function getValidatedOutput(code: string, maxRetries = 2): Promise<ReviewResult> {\n  let lastError = \"\";\n\n  for (let attempt = 0; attempt <= maxRetries; attempt++) {\n    const prompt = attempt === 0\n      ? `Review this code and respond with ONLY valid JSON matching this schema: ${JSON.stringify(ReviewSchema.shape)}\\n\\nCode:\\n${code}`\n      : `Your previous response had a validation error: ${lastError}\\n\\nPlease fix and respond with ONLY valid JSON.`;\n\n    const response = await client.messages.create({\n      model: \"claude-sonnet-4-6-20250514\",\n      max_tokens: 2048,\n      messages: [{ role: \"user\", content: prompt }]\n    });\n\n    const text = response.content[0].text;\n\n    try {\n      // Extract JSON (handle markdown code blocks)\n      const jsonStr = text.includes(\"```\")\n        ? text.match(/```(?:json)?\\s*([\\s\\S]*?)```/)?.[1] || text\n        : text;\n\n      const parsed = JSON.parse(jsonStr.trim());\n      return ReviewSchema.parse(parsed); // Zod validates + types\n    } catch (e) {\n      lastError = e instanceof z.ZodError\n        ? e.errors.map(err => `${err.path.join(\".\")}: ${err.message}`).join(\"; \")\n        : (e as Error).message;\n    }\n  }\n\n  throw new Error(`Failed to get valid output after ${maxRetries + 1} attempts: ${lastError}`);\n}\n\n// =============================================\n// APPROACH 3: tool_choice: \"any\" for multi-output\n// (When you need the model to choose which schema)\n// =============================================\n\nconst outputTools: Anthropic.Tool[] = [\n  {\n    name: \"report_safe\",\n    description: \"Report that the code is safe with no issues\",\n    input_schema: {\n      type: \"object\",\n      properties: { summary: { type: \"string\" } },\n      required: [\"summary\"]\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    name: \"report_issues\",\n    description: \"Report code issues found\",\n    input_schema: {\n      type: \"object\",\n      properties: {\n        findings: {\n          type: \"array\",\n          items: { type: \"object\", properties: {\n            severity: { type: \"string\" },\n            issue: { type: \"string\" }\n          }}\n        }\n      },\n      required: [\"findings\"]\n    }\n  }\n];\n\n// Model chooses the appropriate output schema\nconst response = await client.messages.create({\n  model: \"claude-sonnet-4-6-20250514\",\n  max_tokens: 1024,\n  tools: outputTools,\n  tool_choice: { type: \"any\" }, // Must call ONE of the tools\n  messages: [{ role: \"user\", content: `Review: ${code}` }]\n});', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Use `tool_choice: { type: \"tool\", name: \"your_tool\" }` to FORCE the model to call a specific tool — this guarantees structured output matching your schema. Use `tool_choice: { type: \"any\" }` when the model should choose between multiple output formats.' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### When to Use Which Approach\n\n| Approach | Reliability | Complexity | Best For |\n|----------|------------|------------|----------|\n| tool_choice: tool | 99.9% | Low | Single output schema, production pipelines |\n| tool_choice: any | 99% | Low | Multiple possible output formats |\n| Zod validation loop | 99%+ (with retries) | Medium | Complex schemas with custom validation rules |\n| Prefilled response | ~95% | Low | Quick prototyping, simple JSON |\n| Raw JSON instruction | ~85% | None | Demos only — never production |\n\n### Key Takeaway for Orchestration\n\nIn a multi-agent system, every agent-to-agent message must be structured. If Agent A sends free-form text to Agent B, you\'re relying on Agent B to parse it correctly — which introduces compounding error rates. Use tool_use schemas as the "contracts" between agents. This is the equivalent of typed interfaces in TypeScript — it prevents integration bugs at the boundary.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What is the most reliable way to get structured JSON from Claude?', options: ['Ask for JSON in the system prompt', 'Use tool_choice to force calling a tool with a defined schema', 'Set temperature to 0', 'Use regex to extract JSON from the response'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'tool_choice: { type: \"tool\", name: \"...\" } forces the model to call a specific tool, guaranteeing the output matches your defined JSON schema. This is a first-class API feature, not freeform text generation.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'Why should inter-agent messages use structured schemas?', options: ['To save tokens', 'To prevent compounding parse errors at agent boundaries', 'Because agents can\'t read text', 'To encrypt the messages'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'When agents pass free-form text to each other, each handoff introduces parsing risk. Structured schemas act as typed contracts between agents — like interfaces in TypeScript — eliminating integration bugs at boundaries.' },
              { id: 'q3', question: 'What is a "validation loop" for structured output?', options: ['Running the agent multiple times and picking the best', 'Generating output, validating with a schema, and re-prompting with errors if invalid', 'Using a separate validation service', 'Checking output against a test suite'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'A validation loop follows TAOR: generate (Act), validate with Zod/JSON Schema (Observe), if invalid send the error back (Think), and let the model self-correct (Repeat). This achieves 99%+ reliability.' }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        id: 'langchain',
        title: 'LangChain for Agent Development',
        description: 'Build production agents with chains, tools, and memory',
        icon: '🔗',
        color: '#2d3436',
        order: 8,
        lessons: [
          {
            id: 'langchain-fundamentals',
            moduleId: 'langchain',
            title: 'LangChain Fundamentals',
            description: 'Core concepts: chains, prompts, output parsers, and when to use LangChain vs raw SDK',
            order: 1,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## What is LangChain?\n\nLangChain is a framework for building applications powered by LLMs. It provides:\n\n- **Abstractions** for common patterns (chains, agents, memory)\n- **Integrations** with 100+ tools and services\n- **Composability** — build complex flows from simple components\n\n### When to Use LangChain vs Raw Anthropic SDK\n\n| Scenario | Use | Why |\n|----------|-----|-----|\n| Simple tool use | Anthropic SDK | Less overhead, full control |\n| Complex chains with memory | LangChain | Built-in memory management |\n| Multi-model routing | LangChain | Provider abstraction |\n| RAG pipelines | LangChain | Document loaders, splitters, vector stores |\n| Custom agent with specific needs | Anthropic SDK | Maximum flexibility |\n| Rapid prototyping | LangChain | Pre-built components |\n\n### Core Concepts\n\n1. **Models** — LLM wrappers (ChatAnthropic)\n2. **Prompts** — Templated instructions (ChatPromptTemplate)\n3. **Chains** — Sequences of operations (prompt → model → parser)\n4. **Agents** — LLMs that decide which tools to use\n5. **Memory** — Conversation state management\n6. **Retrievers** — Document search for RAG' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// LangChain setup with Claude\nimport { ChatAnthropic } from "@langchain/anthropic";\nimport { ChatPromptTemplate } from "@langchain/core/prompts";\nimport { StringOutputParser } from "@langchain/core/output_parsers";\nimport { RunnableSequence } from "@langchain/core/runnables";\n\n// Initialize Claude model\nconst model = new ChatAnthropic({\n  model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414",\n  temperature: 0,\n  maxTokens: 4096,\n});\n\n// Create a simple chain: prompt → model → parser\nconst codeReviewChain = RunnableSequence.from([\n  ChatPromptTemplate.fromMessages([\n    ["system", `You are a senior code reviewer. Review the following code for:\n      1. Bugs and logic errors\n      2. Security vulnerabilities\n      3. Performance issues\n      4. Code style\n      Provide a score out of 10 and specific feedback.`],\n    ["human", "Review this code:\\n\\n{code}"]\n  ]),\n  model,\n  new StringOutputParser()\n]);\n\n// Use the chain\nconst review = await codeReviewChain.invoke({\n  code: `function login(user, pass) {\n    const query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE name=\'" + user + "\'";\n    return db.query(query);\n  }`\n});\nconsole.log(review);\n// Output: "Score: 2/10. Critical SQL injection vulnerability..."', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Start with the raw Anthropic SDK for learning. Move to LangChain when you need memory management, RAG pipelines, or complex multi-step chains. Don\'t add LangChain just because — it\'s overhead when a simple API call suffices.' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Installation\n\n```bash\nnpm install @langchain/anthropic @langchain/core langchain\n```\n\nThe `@langchain/anthropic` package provides the Claude integration. `@langchain/core` has the base abstractions. `langchain` has the higher-level chains and agents.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'When should you prefer the raw Anthropic SDK over LangChain?', options: ['Always', 'When you need simple tool use with maximum control', 'When building RAG pipelines', 'When you need memory'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'The raw SDK gives you full control with less overhead — ideal for simple tool use. LangChain adds value when you need memory management, RAG, or complex chains.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'What is a "chain" in LangChain?', options: ['A blockchain connection', 'A sequence of operations (prompt → model → parser)', 'A type of memory', 'A tool definition'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'A chain is a sequence of composable operations. The simplest chain is: prompt template → model → output parser.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'langchain-agents-tools',
            moduleId: 'langchain',
            title: 'LangChain Agents & Tools',
            description: 'Creating agents with tool access using LangChain\'s agent framework',
            order: 2,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## LangChain Agents: LLMs That Use Tools\n\nA LangChain agent is an LLM that:\n1. Receives a task\n2. Decides which tool(s) to call\n3. Executes tools and observes results\n4. Iterates until the task is complete\n\nThis is TAOR implemented through the LangChain framework!\n\n### Agent Types\n\n- **Tool-calling agent** — Uses Claude\'s native tool calling\n- **ReAct agent** — Explicit reasoning + action steps\n- **Plan-and-execute** — Creates plan first, then executes' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Building a development agent with LangChain\nimport { ChatAnthropic } from "@langchain/anthropic";\nimport { createToolCallingAgent, AgentExecutor } from "langchain/agents";\nimport { ChatPromptTemplate } from "@langchain/core/prompts";\nimport { DynamicStructuredTool } from "@langchain/core/tools";\nimport { z } from "zod";\n\n// Define tools\nconst readFileTool = new DynamicStructuredTool({\n  name: "read_file",\n  description: "Read the contents of a file at the given path",\n  schema: z.object({\n    path: z.string().describe("The file path to read")\n  }),\n  func: async ({ path }) => {\n    const fs = await import("fs/promises");\n    return await fs.readFile(path, "utf-8");\n  }\n});\n\nconst runTestsTool = new DynamicStructuredTool({\n  name: "run_tests",\n  description: "Run the test suite and return results",\n  schema: z.object({\n    testPath: z.string().optional().describe("Specific test file to run")\n  }),\n  func: async ({ testPath }) => {\n    const { execSync } = await import("child_process");\n    const cmd = testPath ? `npm test -- ${testPath}` : "npm test";\n    try {\n      return execSync(cmd, { encoding: "utf-8" });\n    } catch (e: any) {\n      return `Tests failed:\\n${e.stdout}\\n${e.stderr}`;\n    }\n  }\n});\n\nconst searchCodeTool = new DynamicStructuredTool({\n  name: "search_code",\n  description: "Search the codebase for a pattern using grep",\n  schema: z.object({\n    pattern: z.string().describe("The regex pattern to search for"),\n    directory: z.string().optional().describe("Directory to search in")\n  }),\n  func: async ({ pattern, directory = "." }) => {\n    const { execSync } = await import("child_process");\n    try {\n      return execSync(`grep -rn "${pattern}" ${directory} --include="*.ts"`, { encoding: "utf-8" });\n    } catch {\n      return "No matches found";\n    }\n  }\n});\n\n// Create the agent\nconst model = new ChatAnthropic({ model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414" });\nconst tools = [readFileTool, runTestsTool, searchCodeTool];\n\nconst prompt = ChatPromptTemplate.fromMessages([\n  ["system", `You are a senior developer agent. Follow TAOR:\n    - THINK before each action\n    - Take ONE action at a time\n    - OBSERVE results carefully\n    - REPEAT until the task is complete and verified`],\n  ["human", "{input}"],\n  ["placeholder", "{agent_scratchpad}"]\n]);\n\nconst agent = createToolCallingAgent({ llm: model, tools, prompt });\nconst executor = new AgentExecutor({ agent, tools, verbose: true });\n\n// Run the agent\nconst result = await executor.invoke({\n  input: "Find all files that import AuthService and check if they handle token expiry correctly"\n});\nconsole.log(result.output);', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'LangChain agents can be opaque. Always set `verbose: true` during development so you can see every TAOR cycle. In production, use LangSmith for tracing.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What does AgentExecutor do in LangChain?', options: ['Defines the tools', 'Runs the TAOR loop — invoking the agent, executing tools, and feeding results back', 'Creates the prompt template', 'Connects to the database'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'AgentExecutor is the runtime loop. It calls the agent (LLM), executes any tool calls, feeds results back, and repeats until the agent finishes — this is the TAOR loop.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'langchain-memory',
            moduleId: 'langchain',
            title: 'Memory & Conversation Management',
            description: 'Give agents long-term context with buffer, summary, and vector memory',
            order: 3,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Agent Memory in LangChain\n\nWithout memory, each agent interaction starts from scratch. Memory types:\n\n| Type | Keeps | Good For |\n|------|-------|----------|\n| **BufferMemory** | Full conversation | Short sessions |\n| **BufferWindowMemory** | Last N messages | Long sessions |\n| **SummaryMemory** | AI-generated summary | Very long sessions |\n| **VectorStoreMemory** | Semantic search over history | Cross-session recall |\n\n### When to Use Each\n\n- **Buffer** → Agent working on a single task (keeps full context)\n- **Window** → Support chat (last 10 exchanges are enough)\n- **Summary** → Multi-hour coding sessions (compress old context)\n- **Vector** → Agent that remembers past tasks and solutions' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Memory-augmented agent\nimport { ChatAnthropic } from "@langchain/anthropic";\nimport { BufferWindowMemory } from "langchain/memory";\nimport { ConversationChain } from "langchain/chains";\nimport { ChatPromptTemplate, MessagesPlaceholder } from "@langchain/core/prompts";\n\n// Buffer Window Memory — keeps last 20 messages\nconst memory = new BufferWindowMemory({\n  k: 20,\n  returnMessages: true,\n  memoryKey: "history"\n});\n\nconst prompt = ChatPromptTemplate.fromMessages([\n  ["system", `You are a development assistant with memory of our conversation.\n    Use past context to give better answers. Reference previous decisions\n    we\'ve made together.`],\n  new MessagesPlaceholder("history"),\n  ["human", "{input}"]\n]);\n\nconst chain = new ConversationChain({\n  llm: new ChatAnthropic({ model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414" }),\n  memory,\n  prompt\n});\n\n// Conversation persists across calls\nawait chain.invoke({ input: "Let\'s use PostgreSQL for the user service" });\n// Later...\nawait chain.invoke({ input: "Now add the database schema" });\n// Agent remembers we chose PostgreSQL!\n\n// Vector Store Memory — semantic recall across sessions\nimport { MemoryVectorStore } from "langchain/vectorstores/memory";\nimport { OpenAIEmbeddings } from "@langchain/openai";\n\nconst vectorMemory = new VectorStoreMemory({\n  vectorStoreRetriever: new MemoryVectorStore(\n    new OpenAIEmbeddings()\n  ).asRetriever(3), // Retrieve top 3 relevant memories\n  memoryKey: "relevant_history"\n});\n\n// Store facts for later retrieval\nawait vectorMemory.saveContext(\n  { input: "What database should we use?" },\n  { output: "We chose PostgreSQL 15 with pgvector extension for embeddings support." }\n);', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'For team agents, use Vector Store Memory to share knowledge across agents. When the Coder agent learns something about the codebase, store it so the Reviewer agent can recall it later.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'Which memory type is best for a coding agent working on a multi-hour refactoring task?', options: ['BufferMemory (full history)', 'SummaryMemory (compressed)', 'No memory needed', 'BufferWindowMemory (last 5 messages)'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'For multi-hour sessions, SummaryMemory compresses old context into summaries, preventing context overflow while retaining key decisions and facts.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'langchain-production',
            moduleId: 'langchain',
            title: 'LangChain + Claude: Production Patterns',
            description: 'Error handling, streaming, callbacks, and tracing for production',
            order: 4,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Production-Ready LangChain\n\n### Streaming Responses\n\nFor interactive agents, stream responses token-by-token:' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Streaming agent output\nimport { ChatAnthropic } from "@langchain/anthropic";\n\nconst model = new ChatAnthropic({\n  model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414",\n  streaming: true\n});\n\n// Stream tokens as they arrive\nconst stream = await executor.stream({ input: "Explain the auth flow" });\n\nfor await (const chunk of stream) {\n  if (chunk.output) {\n    process.stdout.write(chunk.output);\n  }\n  // Also get intermediate steps\n  if (chunk.intermediateSteps) {\n    for (const step of chunk.intermediateSteps) {\n      console.log(`\\n🔧 Tool: ${step.action.tool}`);\n      console.log(`   Input: ${JSON.stringify(step.action.toolInput)}`);\n      console.log(`   Result: ${step.observation.slice(0, 100)}...`);\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// Callbacks for monitoring\nimport { BaseCallbackHandler } from "@langchain/core/callbacks/base";\n\nclass AgentMonitor extends BaseCallbackHandler {\n  name = "agent-monitor";\n\n  handleToolStart(tool: any, input: string) {\n    console.log(`⚡ Tool started: ${tool.name}`);\n    metrics.increment("agent.tool_calls", { tool: tool.name });\n  }\n\n  handleToolError(err: Error) {\n    console.error(`❌ Tool error: ${err.message}`);\n    metrics.increment("agent.tool_errors");\n  }\n\n  handleLLMEnd(output: any) {\n    const tokens = output.llmOutput?.tokenUsage;\n    if (tokens) {\n      metrics.gauge("agent.tokens_used", tokens.totalTokens);\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nconst executor = new AgentExecutor({\n  agent,\n  tools,\n  callbacks: [new AgentMonitor()],\n  maxIterations: 20,       // Safety limit\n  returnIntermediateSteps: true\n});', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'Always set maxIterations on AgentExecutor in production. Without it, a confused agent can loop indefinitely, consuming tokens and money.' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Error Handling Patterns\n\n```typescript\ntry {\n  const result = await executor.invoke({ input: task });\n} catch (error) {\n  if (error.message.includes("rate_limit")) {\n    await sleep(60000);\n    // Retry with backoff\n  } else if (error.message.includes("max_iterations")) {\n    // Agent exceeded step limit — task too complex\n    // Escalate to human or break into sub-tasks\n  } else {\n    // Unexpected error — log and alert\n    logger.error("Agent failed", { error, task });\n  }\n}\n```' }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        id: 'langgraph',
        title: 'LangGraph: Stateful Agent Orchestration',
        description: 'Build complex agent workflows as directed graphs with state',
        icon: '📊',
        color: '#e84393',
        order: 9,
        lessons: [
          {
            id: 'why-langgraph',
            moduleId: 'langgraph',
            title: 'Why LangGraph?',
            description: 'When simple chains aren\'t enough — state machines for agents',
            order: 1,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Beyond Simple Chains\n\nLangChain chains are linear: A → B → C. But real agent workflows need:\n\n- **Conditional routing** — go to different steps based on results\n- **Loops** — retry or iterate until quality threshold met\n- **Parallel execution** — run multiple agents simultaneously\n- **State management** — track accumulated context across steps\n- **Human-in-the-loop** — pause for approval at critical points\n\n**LangGraph** models workflows as directed graphs where:\n- **Nodes** = processing steps (agents, tools, functions)\n- **Edges** = transitions between steps (can be conditional)\n- **State** = shared data that accumulates across the graph\n\n### Mental Model\n\n```\nSimple Chain:     A ──→ B ──→ C ──→ Done\n\nLangGraph:        ┌──→ B ──┐\n                  │        │\n            A ───┤         ├──→ D ──→ Done\n                  │        │     ↑\n                  └──→ C ──┘     │\n                       │         │\n                       └─ (if fails) ─┘\n```\n\nThis is how you build real orchestration — not just calling agents in sequence, but managing complex workflows with branches, loops, and coordination.' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// LangGraph basics — a simple 3-node workflow\nimport { StateGraph, START, END } from "@langchain/langgraph";\nimport { Annotation } from "@langchain/langgraph";\n\n// Define the graph state — what data flows between nodes\nconst AgentState = Annotation.Root({\n  task: Annotation<string>(),\n  plan: Annotation<string[]>({ default: () => [] }),\n  code: Annotation<string>({ default: () => "" }),\n  tests: Annotation<string>({ default: () => "" }),\n  status: Annotation<string>({ default: () => "pending" })\n});\n\n// Define nodes (each is a function that takes state, returns partial state)\nasync function planNode(state: typeof AgentState.State) {\n  const plan = await plannerAgent.invoke(state.task);\n  return { plan: plan.steps };\n}\n\nasync function codeNode(state: typeof AgentState.State) {\n  const code = await coderAgent.invoke({\n    task: state.task,\n    plan: state.plan\n  });\n  return { code: code.output };\n}\n\nasync function testNode(state: typeof AgentState.State) {\n  const result = await testerAgent.invoke({ code: state.code });\n  return {\n    tests: result.output,\n    status: result.passed ? "complete" : "needs_fix"\n  };\n}\n\n// Build the graph\nconst graph = new StateGraph(AgentState)\n  .addNode("plan", planNode)\n  .addNode("code", codeNode)\n  .addNode("test", testNode)\n  .addEdge(START, "plan")\n  .addEdge("plan", "code")\n  .addEdge("code", "test")\n  .addConditionalEdges("test", (state) => {\n    // If tests pass → done. If not → back to code\n    return state.status === "complete" ? END : "code";\n  })\n  .compile();\n\n// Execute\nconst result = await graph.invoke({\n  task: "Add pagination to the users API"\n});\nconsole.log(result.status); // "complete"', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Think of LangGraph as "TAOR at the architecture level." Each node is an agent running TAOR. The graph itself is a higher-level TAOR — it observes node outputs and decides where to route next.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What problem does LangGraph solve that simple LangChain chains cannot?', options: ['Faster execution', 'Conditional routing, loops, and state management', 'Better prompts', 'Lower cost'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'LangGraph adds conditional edges (routing based on results), loops (retry until success), and shared state — essential for real-world workflows that aren\'t purely linear.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'In LangGraph, what is a "node"?', options: ['A database entry', 'A processing step (agent, tool, or function)', 'A user interface element', 'A type of edge'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Nodes are the processing steps in the graph — each one is a function that takes state, does something (call an agent, run a tool, make a decision), and returns updated state.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'langgraph-conditional',
            moduleId: 'langgraph',
            title: 'Conditional Routing & Human-in-the-Loop',
            description: 'Dynamic workflows with branching, approval gates, and interrupts',
            order: 2,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Dynamic Workflows\n\n### Conditional Routing\n\nThe real power of LangGraph is conditional edges — the graph decides the next step based on the current state:\n\n```\n                    ┌── severity: high ──→ [Senior Review]\n[Analyze Code] ───┤── severity: medium ─→ [Auto Review]\n                    └── severity: low ───→ [Auto Approve]\n```\n\n### Human-in-the-Loop\n\nFor critical operations, pause execution and wait for human approval:\n\n```\n[Generate Code] → [Review Gate] ⏸️ → [Deploy]\n                       ↑\n                  Human approves\n```' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Conditional routing + human approval\nimport { StateGraph, START, END, interrupt } from "@langchain/langgraph";\nimport { MemorySaver } from "@langchain/langgraph";\n\nconst DevWorkflow = Annotation.Root({\n  task: Annotation<string>(),\n  code: Annotation<string>({ default: () => "" }),\n  review: Annotation<{ score: number; issues: string[] }>({ default: () => ({ score: 0, issues: [] }) }),\n  approved: Annotation<boolean>({ default: () => false }),\n});\n\nasync function codeNode(state: typeof DevWorkflow.State) {\n  const result = await coderAgent.invoke({ task: state.task });\n  return { code: result.output };\n}\n\nasync function reviewNode(state: typeof DevWorkflow.State) {\n  const review = await reviewerAgent.invoke({ code: state.code });\n  return { review: { score: review.score, issues: review.issues } };\n}\n\nasync function approvalGate(state: typeof DevWorkflow.State) {\n  // INTERRUPT: pause here and wait for human decision\n  const humanDecision = interrupt({\n    question: `Code review score: ${state.review.score}/10.\\n` +\n      `Issues: ${state.review.issues.join(", ")}\\n\\n` +\n      `Approve deployment?`\n  });\n  return { approved: humanDecision === "yes" };\n}\n\nasync function deployNode(state: typeof DevWorkflow.State) {\n  await deployService.deploy(state.code);\n  return {};\n}\n\n// Route based on review score\nfunction routeAfterReview(state: typeof DevWorkflow.State): string {\n  if (state.review.score >= 9) return "deploy";       // Auto-deploy if excellent\n  if (state.review.score >= 7) return "approval";     // Human approval needed\n  return "code";                                       // Score too low, redo\n}\n\nfunction routeAfterApproval(state: typeof DevWorkflow.State): string {\n  return state.approved ? "deploy" : "code";\n}\n\nconst graph = new StateGraph(DevWorkflow)\n  .addNode("code", codeNode)\n  .addNode("review", reviewNode)\n  .addNode("approval", approvalGate)\n  .addNode("deploy", deployNode)\n  .addEdge(START, "code")\n  .addEdge("code", "review")\n  .addConditionalEdges("review", routeAfterReview)\n  .addConditionalEdges("approval", routeAfterApproval)\n  .addEdge("deploy", END)\n  .compile({ checkpointer: new MemorySaver() }); // Persist state for interrupts\n\n// Start execution (will pause at approval gate)\nconst config = { configurable: { thread_id: "task-123" } };\nlet result = await graph.invoke({ task: "Add OAuth2 login" }, config);\n\n// Later: human approves and resumes\nresult = await graph.invoke({ approved: true }, config);', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'Always use a checkpointer (MemorySaver or database-backed) with human-in-the-loop workflows. Without it, the graph state is lost when execution pauses, and you can\'t resume.' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Key Patterns\n\n1. **Quality Gate** — Route to human review if confidence < threshold\n2. **Retry Loop** — Send back to previous node on failure (max 3x)\n3. **Parallel Fan-Out** — Split to multiple nodes, merge results\n4. **Escalation** — If junior agent fails, escalate to senior agent' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What does `interrupt()` do in LangGraph?', options: ['Crashes the program', 'Pauses execution until a human provides input', 'Skips the current node', 'Deletes the state'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'interrupt() pauses the graph execution and waits for external input (usually a human decision). The state is persisted via the checkpointer, allowing resumption later.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'langgraph-multi-agent',
            moduleId: 'langgraph',
            title: 'Multi-Agent Graphs',
            description: 'Build a full development team as a LangGraph workflow',
            order: 3,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## A Development Team as a Graph\n\nThis is the ultimate pattern: your entire team\'s workflow encoded as a LangGraph, with each role as a specialized agent node.\n\n```\n                    ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\n                    │        DEVELOPMENT GRAPH         │\n                    │                                 │\n  Jira Ticket ──→ [Analyzer] ──→ [Planner] ──→ [Coder]\n                                                  │\n                                                  ▼\n                                              [Tester]\n                                                  │\n                                          ┌───────┴────────┐\n                                          │                │\n                                     pass ▼           fail ▼\n                                    [Reviewer]        [Coder] (retry)\n                                          │\n                                     ┌────┴─────┐\n                                     │          │\n                                score≥8 ▼    score<8 ▼\n                                  [PR Creator]  [Coder] (improve)\n                                     │\n                                     ▼\n                                   DONE\n```' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Full multi-agent development graph\nimport { StateGraph, START, END, Annotation } from "@langchain/langgraph";\nimport { ChatAnthropic } from "@langchain/anthropic";\n\nconst TeamState = Annotation.Root({\n  ticket: Annotation<{ id: string; title: string; description: string; criteria: string[] }>(),\n  analysis: Annotation<string>({ default: () => "" }),\n  plan: Annotation<string[]>({ default: () => [] }),\n  code: Annotation<Record<string, string>>({ default: () => ({}) }),\n  testResults: Annotation<{ passed: boolean; output: string }>({ default: () => ({ passed: false, output: "" }) }),\n  reviewScore: Annotation<number>({ default: () => 0 }),\n  reviewFeedback: Annotation<string>({ default: () => "" }),\n  retryCount: Annotation<number>({ default: () => 0 }),\n  prUrl: Annotation<string>({ default: () => "" }),\n});\n\n// Each node is a specialized agent with its own TAOR loop\nasync function analyzerNode(state: typeof TeamState.State) {\n  const model = new ChatAnthropic({ model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414" });\n  const result = await model.invoke([\n    { role: "system", content: `You analyze Jira tickets and extract:\n      - Core requirements\n      - Technical constraints\n      - Acceptance criteria\n      - Risk areas` },\n    { role: "user", content: JSON.stringify(state.ticket) }\n  ]);\n  return { analysis: result.content.toString() };\n}\n\nasync function plannerNode(state: typeof TeamState.State) {\n  const model = new ChatAnthropic({ model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414" });\n  const result = await model.invoke([\n    { role: "system", content: `You are a tech architect. Given an analysis,\n      create an ordered list of implementation steps.\n      Each step must be atomic and testable.` },\n    { role: "user", content: state.analysis }\n  ]);\n  return { plan: JSON.parse(result.content.toString()) };\n}\n\nasync function coderNode(state: typeof TeamState.State) {\n  // This agent has access to file tools and runs TAOR internally\n  const result = await coderAgent.invoke({\n    plan: state.plan,\n    existingCode: state.code,\n    feedback: state.reviewFeedback // Empty on first pass\n  });\n  return { code: result.files };\n}\n\nasync function testerNode(state: typeof TeamState.State) {\n  const result = await testerAgent.invoke({ code: state.code });\n  return { testResults: { passed: result.allPassed, output: result.output } };\n}\n\nasync function reviewerNode(state: typeof TeamState.State) {\n  const model = new ChatAnthropic({ model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414" });\n  const result = await model.invoke([\n    { role: "system", content: `Score this code 1-10. Check: correctness,\n      security, performance, style. Provide specific feedback.` },\n    { role: "user", content: JSON.stringify(state.code) }\n  ]);\n  const review = JSON.parse(result.content.toString());\n  return { reviewScore: review.score, reviewFeedback: review.feedback };\n}\n\n// Routing functions\nfunction routeAfterTests(state: typeof TeamState.State): string {\n  if (state.testResults.passed) return "reviewer";\n  if (state.retryCount >= 3) return END; // Give up after 3 retries\n  return "coder"; // Go back and fix\n}\n\nfunction routeAfterReview(state: typeof TeamState.State): string {\n  if (state.reviewScore >= 8) return "create_pr";\n  if (state.retryCount >= 3) return END;\n  return "coder"; // Improve based on feedback\n}\n\n// Assemble the graph\nconst devTeam = new StateGraph(TeamState)\n  .addNode("analyzer", analyzerNode)\n  .addNode("planner", plannerNode)\n  .addNode("coder", coderNode)\n  .addNode("tester", testerNode)\n  .addNode("reviewer", reviewerNode)\n  .addNode("create_pr", async (state) => {\n    const url = await github.createPR(state.ticket, state.code);\n    return { prUrl: url };\n  })\n  .addEdge(START, "analyzer")\n  .addEdge("analyzer", "planner")\n  .addEdge("planner", "coder")\n  .addEdge("coder", "tester")\n  .addConditionalEdges("tester", routeAfterTests)\n  .addConditionalEdges("reviewer", routeAfterReview)\n  .addEdge("create_pr", END)\n  .compile();\n\n// Execute the full pipeline\nconst result = await devTeam.invoke({\n  ticket: {\n    id: "PROJ-456",\n    title: "Add pagination to users API",\n    description: "...",\n    criteria: ["cursor param", "default limit 20", "next_cursor in response"]\n  }\n});\n\nconsole.log(`PR created: ${result.prUrl}`);', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'agent-demo', content: 'langgraph-team-demo' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Start simple — a 3-node graph (plan → code → test) with one conditional edge. Once that works, add reviewer, PR creator, and retry loops. Complexity should grow incrementally, not all at once.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'In the multi-agent graph, what happens when tests fail?', options: ['The graph stops', 'Execution routes back to the coder node with test output as feedback', 'A new graph is created', 'The tester node retries'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Conditional edges route failed tests back to the coder. The coder receives the test failure output and fixes the issue — this is the TAOR "repeat" step at the graph level.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'langgraph-taor',
            moduleId: 'langgraph',
            title: 'LangGraph + TAOR: The Complete Pattern',
            description: 'Combining structured graphs with disciplined reasoning at every node',
            order: 4,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## The Ultimate Pattern: TAOR Inside LangGraph\n\nThis is the architecture your team should master:\n\n1. **LangGraph** provides the macro structure — what agents to run and in what order\n2. **TAOR** provides the micro behavior — how each agent reasons within its node\n3. **Conditional edges** provide adaptation — the graph responds to results\n\n### The Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────── LANGGRAPH (macro orchestration) ────────────┐\n│                                                        │\n│  ┌─────────┐    ┌─────────┐    ┌─────────┐           │\n│  │  Node A │───→│  Node B │───→│  Node C │           │\n│  │         │    │         │    │         │           │\n│  │ ┌─────┐ │    │ ┌─────┐ │    │ ┌─────┐ │           │\n│  │ │TAOR │ │    │ │TAOR │ │    │ │TAOR │ │           │\n│  │ │loop │ │    │ │loop │ │    │ │loop │ │           │\n│  │ └─────┘ │    │ └─────┘ │    │ └─────┘ │           │\n│  └─────────┘    └─────────┘    └────┬────┘           │\n│                                      │               │\n│                              ┌───────┴──────┐        │\n│                              │              │        │\n│                         success ▼        fail ▼       │\n│                           [END]        [Node B]      │\n│                                                      │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Why This Works\n\n- **LangGraph** handles: routing, retries, state, parallelism\n- **TAOR** handles: accurate reasoning, careful action, verification\n- **Together**: reliable, adaptive, self-correcting agent systems' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Each node runs a full TAOR agent internally\nimport { StateGraph, START, END, Annotation } from "@langchain/langgraph";\nimport Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";\n\nconst client = new Anthropic();\n\n// A TAOR-powered node — it runs multiple TAOR cycles internally\nasync function taorNode(\n  systemPrompt: string,\n  tools: Anthropic.Tool[],\n  maxCycles: number = 10\n) {\n  return async (state: any) => {\n    const messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] = [\n      { role: "user", content: buildTaskFromState(state) }\n    ];\n\n    let cycles = 0;\n    while (cycles < maxCycles) {\n      cycles++;\n\n      // THINK + ACT\n      const response = await client.messages.create({\n        model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414",\n        max_tokens: 4096,\n        thinking: { type: "enabled", budget_tokens: 5000 },\n        system: systemPrompt,\n        tools,\n        messages\n      });\n\n      messages.push({ role: "assistant", content: response.content });\n\n      // REPEAT check\n      if (response.stop_reason === "end_turn") {\n        return extractStateUpdate(response);\n      }\n\n      // OBSERVE\n      if (response.stop_reason === "tool_use") {\n        const toolUse = response.content.find(b => b.type === "tool_use")!;\n        const result = await executeTool(toolUse.name, toolUse.input);\n        messages.push({\n          role: "user",\n          content: [{ type: "tool_result", tool_use_id: toolUse.id, content: result }]\n        });\n      }\n    }\n\n    return { error: "Max cycles reached in TAOR node" };\n  };\n}\n\n// Build the graph with TAOR-powered nodes\nconst workflow = new StateGraph(TeamState)\n  .addNode("planner", taorNode(\n    "You are a planner. Analyze the task and create a step-by-step plan.",\n    [readFileTool, searchCodeTool],\n    5 // Max 5 TAOR cycles for planning\n  ))\n  .addNode("implementer", taorNode(\n    "You are a coder. Implement the plan step by step. Verify each change.",\n    [readFileTool, writeFileTool, runCommandTool],\n    15 // More cycles for implementation\n  ))\n  .addNode("verifier", taorNode(\n    "You are a QA engineer. Run tests and verify all criteria are met.",\n    [readFileTool, runCommandTool],\n    8 // Enough cycles for thorough testing\n  ))\n  .addEdge(START, "planner")\n  .addEdge("planner", "implementer")\n  .addEdge("implementer", "verifier")\n  .addConditionalEdges("verifier", (state) =>\n    state.verified ? END : "implementer"\n  )\n  .compile();', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'This is the pattern used by production AI coding tools. Claude Code itself is essentially a TAOR agent with access to development tools. When you combine multiple such agents in a LangGraph, you get a full autonomous development team.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What does LangGraph handle that TAOR alone cannot?', options: ['Reasoning about problems', 'Routing between agents, retries, and shared state management', 'Using tools', 'Generating code'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'TAOR handles single-agent reasoning. LangGraph adds the macro layer: which agent runs when, what happens on failure, how state flows between agents, and where human approval is needed.' }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        id: 'mcp-deep-dive',
        title: 'MCP Servers Deep Dive',
        description: 'Connect agents to any system via Model Context Protocol',
        icon: '🔌',
        color: '#00b894',
        order: 10,
        lessons: [
          {
            id: 'mcp-architecture',
            moduleId: 'mcp-deep-dive',
            title: 'MCP Protocol Architecture',
            description: 'How MCP works at the protocol level — JSON-RPC, tools, resources',
            order: 1,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Model Context Protocol: Universal Agent Connectivity\n\nMCP standardizes how AI agents connect to external systems. Instead of building custom integrations for each tool, you implement a single protocol.\n\n### Architecture\n\n```\n┌──────────┐      JSON-RPC       ┌──────────────┐      API calls      ┌─────────┐\n│  Claude  │ ←──────────────────→ │  MCP Server  │ ←──────────────────→ │ Service │\n│  (Host)  │   stdio / HTTP+SSE  │  (adapter)   │                      │ (Jira,  │\n└──────────┘                      └──────────────┘                      │ Grafana)│\n                                                                        └─────────┘\n```\n\n### Core Concepts\n\n| Concept | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Server** | A process that exposes tools and resources via MCP |\n| **Tool** | An action the agent can invoke (e.g., `create_jira_ticket`) |\n| **Resource** | Data the agent can read (e.g., `jira://PROJ-123`) |\n| **Transport** | How host and server communicate (stdio or HTTP+SSE) |\n| **Protocol** | JSON-RPC 2.0 messages over the transport |\n\n### How Claude Code Uses MCP\n\nWhen you configure MCP servers in `.claude/settings.json`, Claude Code:\n1. Launches each MCP server as a subprocess\n2. Sends `initialize` to discover available tools\n3. Makes tools available to the agent\n4. Calls tools via JSON-RPC when the agent decides to use them\n5. Returns results to the agent for the OBSERVE step' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// How MCP communication works (simplified)\n// 1. Host sends tool discovery request\n→ { "jsonrpc": "2.0", "method": "tools/list", "id": 1 }\n\n// 2. Server responds with available tools\n← {\n  "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 1,\n  "result": {\n    "tools": [\n      {\n        "name": "jira_get_issue",\n        "description": "Get a Jira issue by ID",\n        "inputSchema": {\n          "type": "object",\n          "properties": {\n            "issue_id": { "type": "string", "description": "e.g., PROJ-123" }\n          },\n          "required": ["issue_id"]\n        }\n      },\n      {\n        "name": "jira_create_issue",\n        "description": "Create a new Jira issue",\n        "inputSchema": { /* ... */ }\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n\n// 3. Agent decides to call a tool\n→ {\n  "jsonrpc": "2.0",\n  "method": "tools/call",\n  "id": 2,\n  "params": {\n    "name": "jira_get_issue",\n    "arguments": { "issue_id": "PROJ-456" }\n  }\n}\n\n// 4. Server executes and returns result\n← {\n  "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 2,\n  "result": {\n    "content": [{\n      "type": "text",\n      "text": "{\\"id\\":\\"PROJ-456\\",\\"summary\\":\\"Add pagination\\",\\"status\\":\\"To Do\\"}"\n    }]\n  }\n}', language: 'json' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'MCP servers are composable — you can connect Claude to Jira + Grafana + Database + Git simultaneously. The agent decides which tool to use based on the task, just like a developer switches between Jira, terminal, and IDE.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What protocol does MCP use for communication?', options: ['REST API', 'GraphQL', 'JSON-RPC 2.0', 'gRPC'], correctIndex: 2, explanation: 'MCP uses JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdio or HTTP+SSE transport. This provides a simple, standardized request/response pattern for tool invocation.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'What\'s the difference between a Tool and a Resource in MCP?', options: ['Tools are faster', 'Tools are actions (do something), Resources are data (read something)', 'Resources are more expensive', 'No difference'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Tools are actions the agent can execute (create ticket, run query). Resources are data the agent can read (ticket contents, dashboard state). This mirrors the ACT vs OBSERVE distinction in TAOR.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'building-mcp-server',
            moduleId: 'mcp-deep-dive',
            title: 'Building a Custom MCP Server',
            description: 'Create your own MCP server to connect Claude to any internal system',
            order: 2,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Build Your Own MCP Server\n\nWant to connect Claude to your internal APIs, databases, or custom tools? Build an MCP server.\n\n### Setup\n\n```bash\nnpm init -y\nnpm install @modelcontextprotocol/sdk zod\nnpm install -D typescript @types/node\n```' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// src/index.ts — A custom MCP server for your internal API\nimport { McpServer } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/mcp.js";\nimport { StdioServerTransport } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js";\nimport { z } from "zod";\n\nconst server = new McpServer({\n  name: "internal-api",\n  version: "1.0.0"\n});\n\n// Define tools with Zod schemas for type safety\nserver.tool(\n  "get_service_status",\n  "Get the health status of an internal service",\n  { service_name: z.string().describe("Name of the service (e.g., auth, payments, users)") },\n  async ({ service_name }) => {\n    const response = await fetch(`https://internal-api.company.com/health/${service_name}`);\n    const data = await response.json();\n    return {\n      content: [{ type: "text", text: JSON.stringify(data, null, 2) }]\n    };\n  }\n);\n\nserver.tool(\n  "query_metrics",\n  "Query Prometheus metrics for a service",\n  {\n    query: z.string().describe("PromQL query"),\n    duration: z.string().optional().describe("Time range, e.g., 1h, 30m")\n  },\n  async ({ query, duration = "1h" }) => {\n    const url = `https://prometheus.company.com/api/v1/query?query=${encodeURIComponent(query)}&time=${duration}`;\n    const response = await fetch(url, {\n      headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.PROM_TOKEN}` }\n    });\n    const data = await response.json();\n    return {\n      content: [{ type: "text", text: JSON.stringify(data.data.result, null, 2) }]\n    };\n  }\n);\n\nserver.tool(\n  "create_deploy",\n  "Trigger a deployment for a service",\n  {\n    service: z.string().describe("Service to deploy"),\n    version: z.string().describe("Version/tag to deploy"),\n    environment: z.enum(["staging", "production"]).describe("Target environment")\n  },\n  async ({ service, version, environment }) => {\n    // Safety check — require confirmation for production\n    if (environment === "production") {\n      return {\n        content: [{\n          type: "text",\n          text: `⚠️ PRODUCTION DEPLOY requested: ${service}@${version}. This requires manual approval in the CI/CD pipeline.`\n        }]\n      };\n    }\n    const result = await triggerDeploy(service, version, environment);\n    return {\n      content: [{ type: "text", text: `Deploy triggered: ${result.id}` }]\n    };\n  }\n);\n\n// Start the server\nconst transport = new StdioServerTransport();\nawait server.connect(transport);', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Connecting to Claude Code\n\nAdd to `.claude/settings.json`:\n\n```json\n{\n  "mcpServers": {\n    "internal-api": {\n      "command": "node",\n      "args": ["./mcp-servers/internal-api/dist/index.js"],\n      "env": {\n        "PROM_TOKEN": "${PROMETHEUS_TOKEN}",\n        "API_KEY": "${INTERNAL_API_KEY}"\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nNow Claude can: check service health, query metrics, and trigger deployments — all through your custom MCP server.' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'Security: Never expose destructive operations without guards. For production deploys, database writes, or anything irreversible, return a confirmation message rather than executing immediately. Let the human-in-the-loop approve.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What package do you use to build an MCP server?', options: ['@anthropic-ai/sdk', '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk', 'langchain', 'express'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'The @modelcontextprotocol/sdk package provides McpServer, transport layers, and tool registration — everything needed to build a custom MCP server.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'mcp-composition',
            moduleId: 'mcp-deep-dive',
            title: 'Composing MCP Servers for Full Automation',
            description: 'Combine Jira + Grafana + Git + Database MCPs for end-to-end workflows',
            order: 3,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## The Power of MCP Composition\n\nWith multiple MCP servers, Claude becomes a development powerhouse:\n\n```\nClaude Code Agent\n    │\n    ├── Jira MCP ─────── Read tickets, create issues, manage sprints\n    ├── Grafana MCP ──── Query metrics, check alerts, view dashboards\n    ├── Git MCP ───────── Create branches, commit, create PRs\n    ├── Database MCP ──── Query schemas, run migrations\n    └── Internal MCP ──── Deploy, check health, manage config\n```\n\n### Real Workflow: Incident Response\n\n1. Grafana alert fires → Claude sees it via Grafana MCP\n2. Claude queries error metrics and logs\n3. Claude searches codebase for relevant code via Git\n4. Claude checks recent deployments\n5. Claude creates a Jira incident ticket\n6. Claude implements a fix and creates a PR\n7. Claude monitors the fix via Grafana after deploy' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Claude Code settings for full development stack\n// .claude/settings.json\n{\n  "mcpServers": {\n    "atlassian": {\n      "command": "npx",\n      "args": ["-y", "@anthropic/mcp-atlassian"],\n      "env": {\n        "JIRA_URL": "https://yourcompany.atlassian.net",\n        "JIRA_EMAIL": "${JIRA_EMAIL}",\n        "JIRA_TOKEN": "${JIRA_TOKEN}",\n        "CONFLUENCE_URL": "https://yourcompany.atlassian.net/wiki",\n        "CONFLUENCE_EMAIL": "${JIRA_EMAIL}",\n        "CONFLUENCE_TOKEN": "${JIRA_TOKEN}"\n      }\n    },\n    "grafana": {\n      "command": "npx",\n      "args": ["-y", "@anthropic/mcp-grafana"],\n      "env": {\n        "GRAFANA_URL": "https://grafana.yourcompany.com",\n        "GRAFANA_API_KEY": "${GRAFANA_TOKEN}"\n      }\n    },\n    "postgres": {\n      "command": "npx",\n      "args": ["-y", "@anthropic/mcp-postgres"],\n      "env": {\n        "DATABASE_URL": "${DATABASE_URL}"\n      }\n    },\n    "internal": {\n      "command": "node",\n      "args": ["./tools/mcp-internal/dist/index.js"],\n      "env": {\n        "API_TOKEN": "${INTERNAL_TOKEN}"\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// Now Claude Code can handle prompts like:\n// "Check Grafana for any alerts on the payments service,\n//  create a Jira ticket if there are issues, and investigate\n//  the root cause in the codebase."', language: 'json' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Each MCP server is independent — you can add/remove servers without affecting others. Start with Jira + Git (most impactful for daily dev work), then add Grafana and database as your team gets comfortable.' },
              { type: 'agent-demo', content: 'mcp-composition-demo' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What happens when Claude has access to multiple MCP servers?', options: ['It can only use one at a time', 'It sees ALL tools from ALL servers and decides which to use based on the task', 'It crashes from too many tools', 'They must be used in order'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Claude sees the combined tool list from all configured MCP servers. During a TAOR cycle, it picks the most relevant tool for the current step — Jira for tickets, Grafana for metrics, Git for code.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'project-ai-config',
            moduleId: 'mcp-deep-dive',
            title: 'Project Configuration Files for AI Tools',
            description: 'CLAUDE.md, copilot-instructions, .cursorrules — configuring AI agents for your team and orchestration',
            order: 4,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Configuring AI Agents at the Project Level\n\nEvery AI coding tool reads project-level configuration files that define how it should behave in YOUR codebase. These files are the bridge between your team\'s standards and AI agent behavior. Getting them right is the difference between an agent that produces code your team rejects and one that matches your conventions perfectly.\n\n### Why Project Config Files Matter for Orchestration\n\nWhen you orchestrate multiple agents (TAOR loops, multi-agent systems, Jira-to-Code pipelines), each agent needs to understand:\n- Your coding standards and patterns\n- Build/test/deploy commands\n- Architecture decisions and boundaries\n- What files to never touch\n- How to verify its work\n\nWithout project config, every agent starts from zero. With it, agents inherit your team\'s collective knowledge from the first turn.\n\n### The Landscape of AI Config Files\n\n| Tool | File(s) | Scope | Format |\n|------|---------|-------|--------|\n| **Claude Code** | `CLAUDE.md` | Hierarchical (root + subdirs) | Markdown |\n| **GitHub Copilot** | `.github/copilot-instructions.md` | Project-wide | Markdown |\n| **Cursor** | `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` | Per-glob pattern | MDC (frontmatter + markdown) |\n| **Windsurf** | `.windsurfrules` | Project-wide | Markdown |\n| **Aider** | `.aider.conf.yml` + conventions | Project-wide | YAML |\n\n### Claude Code: CLAUDE.md (The Most Powerful)\n\nClaude Code has the richest configuration system with **hierarchical scoping**:\n\n```\nproject-root/\n├── CLAUDE.md                    ← Project-wide rules\n├── src/\n│   ├── CLAUDE.md                ← Overrides/extends for src/\n│   ├── api/\n│   │   └── CLAUDE.md            ← API-specific conventions\n│   └── frontend/\n│       └── CLAUDE.md            ← Frontend-specific rules\n└── ~/.claude/\n    ├── CLAUDE.md                ← User-wide preferences\n    └── projects/<hash>/\n        └── CLAUDE.md            ← User-specific project context\n```\n\n**Scoping rules:**\n- Subdirectory CLAUDE.md files augment (don\'t replace) the parent\n- When working in `src/api/`, Claude sees: root + src + api CLAUDE.md\n- User-level files add personal preferences without polluting the team file\n- The `.claude/settings.local.json` file handles per-user MCP server configs' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// ============================================\n// Example: Root CLAUDE.md for a team project\n// ============================================\n\n// File: CLAUDE.md (project root)\n`\n# Project: PaymentService\n\n## Build & Test\n- Build: `npm run build`\n- Test: `npm test`\n- Lint: `npm run lint`\n- Single test: `npm test -- --grep "test name"`\n\n## Architecture\n- Monorepo with packages/ directory\n- Backend: NestJS + TypeScript strict mode\n- Frontend: Angular 19 standalone components\n- Database: PostgreSQL with Prisma ORM\n- Auth: OAuth2 PKCE via internal auth service\n\n## Conventions\n- All functions must have JSDoc with @param and @returns\n- Use Result<T, E> pattern for error handling (never throw)\n- API routes follow /api/v{N}/{resource} pattern\n- Tests colocated with source: foo.ts → foo.spec.ts\n- No barrel exports (index.ts re-exports)\n\n## Boundaries\n- NEVER modify files in packages/shared without team review\n- NEVER commit .env files or hardcode secrets\n- NEVER change database migrations after they\'ve been applied\n- Always run tests before marking a task complete\n\n## Agent Instructions\n- When implementing a Jira ticket, read the full ticket first (use MCP)\n- After coding, run the test suite and fix any failures\n- Create atomic commits with conventional commit messages\n- If a task requires DB changes, create a migration with Prisma\n`\n\n// ============================================\n// Example: .github/copilot-instructions.md\n// ============================================\n\n// File: .github/copilot-instructions.md\n`\nThis is a TypeScript NestJS backend.\nUse strict types, never use \'any\'.\nAll functions need JSDoc comments.\nUse the Result pattern for error handling.\nTests use Jest with describe/it structure.\nDatabase access goes through Prisma repositories.\n`\n\n// ============================================\n// Example: .cursor/rules/api-routes.mdc\n// ============================================\n\n// File: .cursor/rules/api-routes.mdc\n`\n---\ndescription: Rules for API route handlers\nglobs: [\"src/api/**/*.ts\", \"src/routes/**/*.ts\"]\nalwaysApply: false\n---\n\n- All route handlers must validate input with Zod schemas\n- Return standardized responses: { data, error, meta }\n- Use guards for authentication, not inline checks\n- Log all errors with correlation IDs\n`', language: 'markdown' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Write your CLAUDE.md like onboarding docs for a new senior developer who is fast but unfamiliar with your specific conventions. Don\'t explain basic TypeScript — explain YOUR project\'s patterns, boundaries, and the "why" behind non-obvious decisions.' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### How Config Files Power AI Orchestration\n\nProject config files aren\'t just for individual coding sessions — they\'re critical infrastructure for multi-agent orchestration:\n\n**1. Agent Specialization via Subdirectory Configs**\n\nIn a multi-agent system, different agents work on different parts of the codebase. Subdirectory CLAUDE.md files ensure each agent follows the right conventions:\n\n```\nsrc/api/CLAUDE.md      → "API agent" knows REST patterns, validation rules\nsrc/frontend/CLAUDE.md → "UI agent" knows component structure, state management\nsrc/infra/CLAUDE.md    → "DevOps agent" knows deployment patterns, env vars\n```\n\n**2. Orchestrator Context**\n\nThe root CLAUDE.md gives the orchestrator agent the full picture — build commands, architecture overview, and boundaries. This lets it plan effectively and delegate to specialists.\n\n**3. Guardrails for Autonomous Agents**\n\nThe "NEVER" rules in CLAUDE.md act as hard guardrails. When agents run autonomously (Jira-to-Code pipelines, nightly refactoring), these boundaries prevent them from making dangerous changes.\n\n**4. Verification Commands**\n\nBuild/test commands in CLAUDE.md let agents self-verify. After making changes, the agent runs `npm test` — if it fails, the TAOR loop kicks in and the agent fixes the issue. Without these commands documented, agents can\'t close the observe loop.\n\n**5. Cross-Tool Portability**\n\nA team using both Claude Code and GitHub Copilot can maintain parallel configs. The same conventions go into both CLAUDE.md and copilot-instructions.md. Some teams auto-generate one from the other.\n\n### Key Differences Between Tools\n\n| Feature | Claude Code | GitHub Copilot | Cursor |\n|---------|-------------|----------------|--------|\n| Hierarchical dirs | Yes (subdirs inherit) | No (single file) | Partial (glob-based) |\n| User-level config | Yes (~/.claude/) | No | Yes (~/.cursor/) |\n| MCP server config | Yes (settings.json) | No equivalent | No equivalent |\n| Conditional rules | Via subdirectory | No | Yes (globs in frontmatter) |\n| Memory/persistence | Yes (memory files) | No | No |\n| Agent orchestration hooks | Yes (hooks in settings) | No | No |\n\nClaude Code is the only tool with full orchestration support — hierarchical configs, MCP servers, persistent memory, and hooks make it a complete agent platform. The others are excellent for inline code completion but lack the infrastructure for autonomous multi-agent workflows.' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'Don\'t put secrets in ANY of these files — they are committed to the repo. Use environment variable references (${VAR_NAME}) and document which env vars are needed in a separate setup guide.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'Why does Claude Code support hierarchical CLAUDE.md files in subdirectories?', options: ['For file organization only', 'So different agents working on different parts of the codebase get specialized context', 'Because one file would be too large', 'It\'s a legacy feature'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Hierarchical configs enable agent specialization. An API agent in src/api/ gets API-specific conventions automatically, while a frontend agent in src/frontend/ gets UI patterns. This is essential for multi-agent orchestration where different agents handle different domains.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'How do project config files enable the TAOR "Observe" step for autonomous agents?', options: ['They contain test results', 'They document build/test commands that agents run to verify their changes', 'They automatically run tests', 'They are read-only'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Build and test commands documented in CLAUDE.md let agents self-verify (Observe step). After making changes, the agent runs the test command — if tests fail, the TAOR loop continues with self-correction. Without documented commands, agents cannot close the verification loop.' },
              { id: 'q3', question: 'What is the key advantage of Claude Code over GitHub Copilot for agent orchestration?', options: ['Better code completion', 'Hierarchical configs, MCP servers, persistent memory, and hooks — full orchestration infrastructure', 'It\'s faster', 'It supports more languages'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Claude Code provides the complete infrastructure for autonomous agents: hierarchical project configs for specialization, MCP servers for external tool access, persistent memory across sessions, and hooks for workflow automation. Copilot focuses on inline completion without orchestration capabilities.' }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        id: 'rag',
        title: 'RAG: Retrieval-Augmented Generation',
        description: 'Ground agents with relevant knowledge from your codebase and docs',
        icon: '📚',
        color: '#6c5ce7',
        order: 11,
        lessons: [
          {
            id: 'rag-fundamentals',
            moduleId: 'rag',
            title: 'RAG Fundamentals',
            description: 'Why agents need retrieval, and when to use RAG vs long context',
            order: 1,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## What is RAG?\n\nRetrieval-Augmented Generation = **Find relevant information, then generate a response using it.**\n\n### The Problem RAG Solves\n\nLLMs have knowledge cutoffs and limited context windows. RAG lets agents:\n- Access up-to-date information\n- Search large codebases (millions of lines)\n- Ground responses in actual documentation\n- Reduce hallucination by providing source material\n\n### RAG vs Long Context\n\n| Approach | Pros | Cons | Use When |\n|----------|------|------|----------|\n| **RAG** | Scales to any corpus size, focused retrieval | Requires infrastructure, can miss relevant docs | Corpus > 200K tokens, need precision |\n| **Long Context** | Simple, no infrastructure | Limited to 200K tokens, expensive | Small corpus, need full picture |\n| **Hybrid** | Best of both | Most complex | Production systems |\n\n### The RAG Pipeline\n\n```\n┌───────────┐     ┌──────────┐     ┌──────────┐     ┌──────────┐\n│  Index    │     │  Query   │     │ Retrieve │     │ Generate │\n│           │     │          │     │          │     │          │\n│ docs ──→  │     │ user Q ──│──→  │ top-K ───│──→  │ LLM +    │\n│ chunks ──→│     │ embed ───│──→  │ similar  │     │ context  │\n│ embed ──→ │     │          │     │ chunks   │     │ = answer │\n│ store     │     └──────────┘     └──────────┘     └──────────┘\n└───────────┘\n```' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Basic RAG pipeline with LangChain\nimport { ChatAnthropic } from "@langchain/anthropic";\nimport { OpenAIEmbeddings } from "@langchain/openai";\nimport { MemoryVectorStore } from "langchain/vectorstores/memory";\nimport { RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter } from "langchain/text_splitter";\nimport { createStuffDocumentsChain } from "langchain/chains/combine_documents";\nimport { ChatPromptTemplate } from "@langchain/core/prompts";\n\n// 1. LOAD documents\nconst documents = await loadCodebase("./src"); // Your code files\n\n// 2. SPLIT into chunks\nconst splitter = new RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter({\n  chunkSize: 1000,\n  chunkOverlap: 200,\n  separators: ["\\nfunction ", "\\nclass ", "\\nexport ", "\\n\\n", "\\n"]\n});\nconst chunks = await splitter.splitDocuments(documents);\n\n// 3. EMBED and store\nconst embeddings = new OpenAIEmbeddings();\nconst vectorStore = await MemoryVectorStore.fromDocuments(chunks, embeddings);\n\n// 4. RETRIEVE relevant chunks\nconst retriever = vectorStore.asRetriever({\n  k: 5, // Return top 5 most relevant chunks\n  searchType: "similarity"\n});\n\n// 5. GENERATE with context\nconst model = new ChatAnthropic({ model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414" });\n\nconst prompt = ChatPromptTemplate.fromMessages([\n  ["system", `You are a code expert. Answer based ONLY on the provided context.\n    If the context doesn\'t contain the answer, say so.\n    \n    Context:\n    {context}`],\n  ["human", "{input}"]\n]);\n\nconst chain = await createStuffDocumentsChain({ llm: model, prompt });\n\n// Usage\nconst relevantDocs = await retriever.invoke("How does authentication work?");\nconst answer = await chain.invoke({\n  input: "How does authentication work?",\n  context: relevantDocs\n});\nconsole.log(answer);', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'For codebases, use code-aware splitters that respect function/class boundaries. Splitting mid-function produces useless chunks. LangChain\'s RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter with code separators handles this well.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'When should you use RAG instead of just sending everything in the context window?', options: ['Always', 'When your corpus is larger than the context window or you need precision', 'Only for chat applications', 'RAG is always worse than long context'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'RAG is essential when your knowledge base exceeds the context window (200K tokens for Claude). It\'s also better for precision — retrieving only relevant chunks reduces noise and improves answer quality.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'What is "chunking" in RAG?', options: ['Splitting API responses', 'Breaking documents into smaller pieces for embedding and retrieval', 'Compressing the model', 'A type of caching'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Chunking splits large documents into smaller pieces (typically 500-2000 characters). Each chunk is embedded as a vector and stored for similarity search. The granularity affects retrieval quality.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'rag-codebase',
            moduleId: 'rag',
            title: 'RAG for Codebase Understanding',
            description: 'Index your entire codebase so agents can find and understand any code',
            order: 2,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Making Agents Understand Your Codebase\n\nThe dream: an agent that knows your entire codebase as well as your senior devs do. RAG makes this possible.\n\n### Code-Specific Challenges\n\n1. **Semantic chunking** — split at function/class boundaries, not arbitrary character counts\n2. **Context preservation** — include imports, types, and comments with each chunk\n3. **Multi-level indexing** — index at file, function, and class levels\n4. **Freshness** — re-index when code changes (git hooks)\n\n### Indexing Strategy\n\n```\nLevel 1: File summaries (what each file does)\nLevel 2: Function/class level (individual units)\nLevel 3: Cross-reference index (who calls what)\n```' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Code-aware RAG indexer\nimport { parse } from "@typescript-eslint/typescript-estree";\nimport { ChatAnthropic } from "@langchain/anthropic";\nimport { Document } from "@langchain/core/documents";\n\ninterface CodeChunk {\n  content: string;\n  metadata: {\n    filePath: string;\n    type: "function" | "class" | "interface" | "file_summary";\n    name: string;\n    startLine: number;\n    endLine: number;\n    imports: string[];\n  };\n}\n\n// Parse TypeScript files into semantic chunks\nfunction chunkTypeScriptFile(filePath: string, content: string): CodeChunk[] {\n  const chunks: CodeChunk[] = [];\n  const ast = parse(content, { loc: true, range: true });\n\n  for (const node of ast.body) {\n    if (node.type === "FunctionDeclaration" || \n        node.type === "ExportNamedDeclaration") {\n      const funcContent = content.slice(node.range![0], node.range![1]);\n      chunks.push({\n        content: funcContent,\n        metadata: {\n          filePath,\n          type: "function",\n          name: extractName(node),\n          startLine: node.loc!.start.line,\n          endLine: node.loc!.end.line,\n          imports: extractImports(ast)\n        }\n      });\n    }\n    // Similar for classes, interfaces...\n  }\n\n  return chunks;\n}\n\n// Generate file-level summaries using Claude\nasync function generateFileSummary(filePath: string, content: string): Promise<CodeChunk> {\n  const model = new ChatAnthropic({ model: "claude-opus-4-6-20250414" });\n  const summary = await model.invoke([\n    { role: "system", content: "Summarize this code file in 2-3 sentences. Focus on what it does, not how." },\n    { role: "user", content: `File: ${filePath}\\n\\n${content}` }\n  ]);\n\n  return {\n    content: summary.content.toString(),\n    metadata: {\n      filePath, type: "file_summary", name: filePath,\n      startLine: 0, endLine: 0, imports: []\n    }\n  };\n}\n\n// RAG-powered code search for agents\nasync function codeRAGSearch(query: string) {\n  // Search at multiple levels for comprehensive results\n  const fileSummaries = await vectorStore.similaritySearch(query, 3, {\n    filter: { type: "file_summary" }\n  });\n  const functions = await vectorStore.similaritySearch(query, 5, {\n    filter: { type: "function" }\n  });\n\n  return { fileSummaries, functions };\n}', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'Re-index on every git push using a post-commit hook. Stale indexes lead to agents referencing deleted or renamed functions — a common source of hallucination.' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Agent with RAG: The Pattern\n\n```typescript\n// Agent TAOR loop enhanced with RAG\n// THINK: "I need to understand how payments work"\n// ACT: Search RAG index for "payment processing"\n// OBSERVE: Found payment.service.ts, stripe.client.ts\n// THINK: "Now I know the structure. Let me read the specific files."\n// ACT: Read payment.service.ts\n// OBSERVE: Uses Stripe webhook pattern\n// ... continue with informed actions\n```\n\nRAG helps agents THINK better by giving them relevant context before they ACT.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'Why is code-aware chunking important?', options: ['It makes chunks smaller', 'Splitting at function/class boundaries preserves semantic meaning', 'It\'s faster to process', 'It reduces storage costs'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Splitting mid-function creates chunks that lack context. Code-aware chunking ensures each chunk is a complete semantic unit (a function, class, or interface) that makes sense on its own.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'rag-agents',
            moduleId: 'rag',
            title: 'RAG + Agents: Autonomous Knowledge Workers',
            description: 'Agents that retrieve context before acting — Self-RAG and adaptive retrieval',
            order: 3,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Self-RAG: Agents That Know When to Retrieve\n\nThe most powerful pattern: agents that decide WHEN to search for context, not just agents that always search.\n\n### Self-RAG Pattern\n\n```\nAgent receives task\n    │\n    ▼\nTHINK: "Do I have enough context to answer/act?"\n    │\n    ├── YES → Act directly\n    │\n    └── NO → Retrieve relevant context → Then act with context\n```\n\nThis is TAOR applied to knowledge retrieval:\n- **THINK**: Do I need more information?\n- **ACT**: Search the knowledge base\n- **OBSERVE**: Is this context sufficient?\n- **REPEAT**: If not, refine the search query and try again' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Self-RAG agent — retrieves only when needed\nimport Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";\n\nconst client = new Anthropic();\n\nconst SELF_RAG_PROMPT = `You are a development agent with access to a codebase search tool.\n\nBefore taking any coding action:\n1. Ask yourself: "Do I have enough context about the relevant code?"\n2. If NO: use the search_codebase tool to find relevant code\n3. If YES: proceed with your action\n\nAfter retrieving context:\n1. Verify it\'s relevant to your current task\n2. If not relevant enough, refine your search query\n3. Only act once you have sufficient understanding\n\nNever modify code you haven\'t read and understood first.`;\n\nconst tools: Anthropic.Tool[] = [\n  {\n    name: "search_codebase",\n    description: "Semantic search over the codebase. Returns relevant code snippets. Use when you need to understand how something works before making changes.",\n    input_schema: {\n      type: "object",\n      properties: {\n        query: { type: "string", description: "Natural language description of what you\'re looking for" },\n        scope: { type: "string", enum: ["functions", "classes", "files", "all"], description: "What level to search at" }\n      },\n      required: ["query"]\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    name: "read_file",\n    description: "Read a specific file after finding it via search",\n    input_schema: {\n      type: "object",\n      properties: { path: { type: "string" } },\n      required: ["path"]\n    }\n  },\n  {\n    name: "write_file",\n    description: "Write changes to a file",\n    input_schema: {\n      type: "object",\n      properties: { path: { type: "string" }, content: { type: "string" } },\n      required: ["path", "content"]\n    }\n  }\n];\n\n// The search_codebase tool implementation uses RAG\nasync function executeSearchCodebase(query: string, scope: string = "all") {\n  const results = await vectorStore.similaritySearch(query, 5, {\n    filter: scope !== "all" ? { type: scope } : undefined\n  });\n  \n  return results.map(doc => \n    `--- ${doc.metadata.filePath}:${doc.metadata.startLine} (${doc.metadata.type}: ${doc.metadata.name}) ---\\n${doc.pageContent}`\n  ).join("\\n\\n");\n}\n\n// Agent naturally integrates RAG into its TAOR loop:\n// "Fix the authentication bug"\n// THINK: I don\'t know how auth works in this codebase\n// ACT: search_codebase("authentication login flow")\n// OBSERVE: Found auth.service.ts with JWT validation\n// THINK: The bug might be in token validation. Let me read the full file.\n// ACT: read_file("src/services/auth.service.ts")\n// OBSERVE: Found the issue - token expiry check uses wrong comparison\n// THINK: I know how to fix this now\n// ACT: write_file("src/services/auth.service.ts", fixedContent)\n// OBSERVE: File written. Let me verify.\n// ACT: run_tests()\n// OBSERVE: All tests pass ✓\n// DONE', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'Don\'t make agents ALWAYS retrieve. If the agent already has sufficient context (e.g., it just read the file), forced retrieval wastes tokens and slows execution. Let the agent decide via TAOR thinking.' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'The best agent architecture: RAG for exploration (finding what\'s relevant), then direct file reading for implementation (getting the full picture). Search first, read second, write third.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What is "Self-RAG"?', options: ['An agent that builds its own database', 'An agent that decides WHEN to retrieve, not always retrieving', 'A RAG system without an LLM', 'A caching strategy'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Self-RAG means the agent intelligently decides when retrieval is needed. It asks "Do I have enough context?" and only searches when the answer is no. This is TAOR\'s THINK step applied to knowledge retrieval.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'hallucination-prevention',
            moduleId: 'rag',
            title: 'Hallucination Detection & Prevention',
            description: 'Why LLMs hallucinate, detection strategies, grounding techniques, and verification patterns',
            order: 4,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## Why LLMs Hallucinate\n\nHallucination is when an LLM generates confident-sounding information that is factually incorrect. For agent orchestration, this is dangerous — a hallucinating agent might call the wrong API, reference a non-existent file, or make changes based on invented requirements.\n\n### Types of Hallucination\n\n**Factual fabrication**: Inventing facts (\"The function getUserById is on line 42\" when it doesn\'t exist)\n\n**Confident uncertainty**: Presenting guesses as certainties (\"This will fix the bug\" when it hasn\'t verified)\n\n**Context confusion**: Mixing up information from different parts of the conversation\n\n**Capability hallucination**: Claiming to have done something it hasn\'t (\"I\'ve updated the file\" when the tool call failed)\n\n### Why It Happens\n\nLLMs are trained to produce plausible text, not verified facts. They don\'t have a \"confidence\" signal — everything comes out with equal confidence. Key causes:\n\n1. **No ground truth**: The model generates from patterns, not a database of facts\n2. **Pressure to answer**: The model prefers giving an answer over saying \"I don\'t know\"\n3. **Training distribution**: If patterns in training data suggest an answer, the model will produce it\n4. **Long context drift**: The further from the relevant context, the more likely hallucination\n\n### Prevention Strategies\n\n| Strategy | How It Works | Effectiveness |\n|----------|-------------|---------------|\n| RAG (grounding) | Provide relevant docs in context | High — model cites sources |\n| Tool verification | Agent must use tools to verify claims | Very high — reality check |\n| Ask for sources | \"Cite the exact file and line\" | Medium — forces specificity |\n| Confidence prompting | \"If unsure, say I don\'t know\" | Medium — reduces but doesn\'t eliminate |\n| Multi-agent verification | Second agent fact-checks the first | High — independent verification |\n| Extended thinking | More reasoning tokens = less hallucination | High — self-checking |\n| TAOR Observe step | Always verify after acting | Very high — catches hallucinations post-action |' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Hallucination detection and prevention patterns\nimport Anthropic from \"@anthropic-ai/sdk\";\n\nconst client = new Anthropic();\n\n// Pattern 1: Grounding with source verification\nasync function groundedAnswer(question: string, sources: string[]) {\n  const response = await client.messages.create({\n    model: \"claude-sonnet-4-6-20250514\",\n    max_tokens: 2048,\n    system: `You are a technical assistant. RULES:\n1. ONLY answer based on the provided sources\n2. For every claim, cite [Source N] where N is the source index\n3. If the sources don\'t contain the answer, say \"Not found in provided context\"\n4. NEVER infer or guess beyond what the sources explicitly state\n5. If partially covered, state what you know and what is uncertain`,\n    messages: [{\n      role: \"user\",\n      content: `Sources:\\n${sources.map((s, i) => `[Source ${i}]: ${s}`).join(\"\\n\\n\")}\\n\\nQuestion: ${question}`\n    }]\n  });\n  return response.content[0].text;\n}\n\n// Pattern 2: Multi-agent verification\nasync function verifiedClaim(claim: string, context: string): Promise<{\n  isValid: boolean;\n  confidence: number;\n  evidence: string;\n}> {\n  // First agent makes the claim, second agent verifies it\n  const verification = await client.messages.create({\n    model: \"claude-sonnet-4-6-20250514\",\n    max_tokens: 500,\n    tools: [{\n      name: \"verify_claim\",\n      description: \"Verify whether a claim is supported by the evidence\",\n      input_schema: {\n        type: \"object\",\n        properties: {\n          isValid: { type: \"boolean\", description: \"Is the claim supported?\" },\n          confidence: { type: \"number\", description: \"0-1 confidence score\" },\n          evidence: { type: \"string\", description: \"Quote from context that supports or contradicts\" }\n        },\n        required: [\"isValid\", \"confidence\", \"evidence\"]\n      }\n    }],\n    tool_choice: { type: \"tool\", name: \"verify_claim\" },\n    messages: [{\n      role: \"user\",\n      content: `Context:\\n${context}\\n\\nClaim to verify: \"${claim}\"\\n\\nIs this claim factually supported by the context? Be strict.`\n    }]\n  });\n\n  const result = verification.content.find(b => b.type === \"tool_use\")!;\n  return result.input as any;\n}\n\n// Pattern 3: TAOR Observe step — verify after every action\nasync function verifiedToolUse(agent: any, toolName: string, result: string) {\n  // After getting a tool result, verify the agent\'s interpretation\n  const check = await client.messages.create({\n    model: \"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",  // Cheap verification\n    max_tokens: 200,\n    messages: [{\n      role: \"user\",\n      content: `The agent called \"${toolName}\" and received:\\n${result.slice(0, 2000)}\\n\\nDoes this result actually exist and make sense? Answer YES or NO with brief reason.`\n    }]\n  });\n\n  const answer = check.content[0].text;\n  if (answer.startsWith(\"NO\")) {\n    throw new Error(`Hallucination detected: ${answer}`);\n  }\n}', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'The single most effective anti-hallucination pattern for agents: NEVER let the agent claim something without verifying through a tool. If it says \"the function is on line 42\" — make it read_file and confirm. The TAOR Observe step is your hallucination firewall.' },
              { type: 'warning', content: 'Hallucination is most dangerous when the agent is CONFIDENT AND WRONG. Watch for phrases like \"I\'ve verified that...\" or \"The file contains...\" without a preceding tool call. If there\'s no tool_use in the message history that confirms the claim, treat it as potentially hallucinated.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'What is the most effective way to prevent agent hallucination?', options: ['Use a lower temperature', 'Require the agent to verify claims through tool calls (TAOR Observe step)', 'Use a larger model', 'Add \"don\'t hallucinate\" to the prompt'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Tool-based verification forces the agent to ground its claims in reality. The TAOR Observe step ensures every action result is checked. This is far more reliable than prompt-based approaches which merely reduce but don\'t eliminate hallucination.' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'What is "capability hallucination"?', options: ['The model claiming it can\'t do something it can', 'The model claiming to have done something it hasn\'t (e.g., saying it updated a file when the tool call failed)', 'The model using too many tools', 'The model inventing new tools'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'Capability hallucination is when the model claims to have performed an action that didn\'t actually succeed. This is especially dangerous in agents where a failed tool call might be followed by the model saying \"Done! I\'ve updated the file.\" Always check tool_result for actual success.' }
            ]
          },
          {
            id: 'agent-observability',
            moduleId: 'rag',
            title: 'Agent Observability & Debugging',
            description: 'Tracing agent execution, LangSmith integration, debugging multi-agent systems, and production monitoring',
            order: 5,
            content: [
              { type: 'text', content: '## You Can\'t Debug What You Can\'t See\n\nAI agents are non-deterministic. The same input can produce different tool call sequences, different reasoning paths, and different outcomes. Traditional debugging (set breakpoint, inspect state) doesn\'t work. You need observability — the ability to trace and replay agent execution.\n\n### What to Observe\n\n1. **Full message history**: Every user/assistant/tool message in order\n2. **Tool calls and results**: What was called, with what params, what came back\n3. **Token usage per step**: Where are you spending the most tokens?\n4. **Latency per step**: Which tool calls are slow?\n5. **Decision points**: Where did the agent choose path A over path B?\n6. **Error recovery**: How many retries? Did it self-correct?\n7. **Final outcome**: Did it succeed? How many iterations?\n\n### Tracing Architecture\n\n```\nAgent Loop\n  │\n  ├── Each iteration:\n  │   ├── Log: thinking / reasoning\n  │   ├── Log: tool_use (name, params)\n  │   ├── Log: tool_result (output, latency)\n  │   ├── Log: token count (input + output)\n  │   └── Log: decision (continue / stop / error)\n  │\n  └── Summary:\n      ├── Total iterations\n      ├── Total tokens / cost\n      ├── Total latency\n      ├── Success / failure\n      └── Tool call breakdown\n```\n\n### Tools for Agent Observability\n\n| Tool | Type | Best For |\n|------|------|----------|\n| **LangSmith** | SaaS platform | LangChain/LangGraph apps, visual trace UI |\n| **OpenTelemetry** | Open standard | Custom agents, distributed tracing |\n| **Braintrust** | Eval platform | Evaluation + tracing combined |\n| **Arize Phoenix** | Open source | Local development, quick debugging |\n| **Custom logging** | DIY | Full control, simple agents |' },
              { type: 'code', content: '// Agent observability with structured tracing\nimport Anthropic from \"@anthropic-ai/sdk\";\n\n// Trace structure for agent execution\ninterface AgentTrace {\n  traceId: string;\n  taskDescription: string;\n  startTime: number;\n  endTime?: number;\n  steps: TraceStep[];\n  totalTokens: { input: number; output: number };\n  totalCost: number;\n  outcome: \"success\" | \"failure\" | \"timeout\";\n}\n\ninterface TraceStep {\n  stepIndex: number;\n  timestamp: number;\n  type: \"thinking\" | \"tool_call\" | \"tool_result\" | \"decision\" | \"error\";\n  content: {\n    toolName?: string;\n    toolInput?: unknown;\n    toolOutput?: string;\n    reasoning?: string;\n    error?: string;\n    tokensUsed?: { input: number; output: number };\n    latencyMs?: number;\n  };\n}\n\n// Observable agent wrapper\nclass ObservableAgent {\n  private trace: AgentTrace;\n  private client = new Anthropic();\n\n  constructor(taskDescription: string) {\n    this.trace = {\n      traceId: crypto.randomUUID(),\n      taskDescription,\n      startTime: Date.now(),\n      steps: [],\n      totalTokens: { input: 0, output: 0 },\n      totalCost: 0,\n      outcome: \"failure\"\n    };\n  }\n\n  private log(step: Omit<TraceStep, \"stepIndex\" | \"timestamp\">) {\n    this.trace.steps.push({\n      ...step,\n      stepIndex: this.trace.steps.length,\n      timestamp: Date.now()\n    });\n  }\n\n  async run(task: string, tools: Anthropic.Tool[]) {\n    const messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] = [\n      { role: \"user\", content: task }\n    ];\n\n    let iterations = 0;\n    while (iterations < 30) {\n      iterations++;\n      const stepStart = Date.now();\n\n      const response = await this.client.messages.create({\n        model: \"claude-sonnet-4-6-20250514\",\n        max_tokens: 4096,\n        tools,\n        messages\n      });\n\n      // Track tokens\n      this.trace.totalTokens.input += response.usage.input_tokens;\n      this.trace.totalTokens.output += response.usage.output_tokens;\n\n      // Log thinking\n      const textBlock = response.content.find(b => b.type === \"text\");\n      if (textBlock) {\n        this.log({\n          type: \"thinking\",\n          content: { reasoning: textBlock.text.slice(0, 500) }\n        });\n      }\n\n      messages.push({ role: \"assistant\", content: response.content });\n\n      if (response.stop_reason === \"end_turn\") {\n        this.trace.outcome = \"success\";\n        break;\n      }\n\n      // Log and execute tool calls\n      const toolUses = response.content.filter(b => b.type === \"tool_use\");\n      const toolResults: Anthropic.ToolResultBlockParam[] = [];\n\n      for (const toolUse of toolUses) {\n        this.log({\n          type: \"tool_call\",\n          content: {\n            toolName: toolUse.name,\n            toolInput: toolUse.input,\n            latencyMs: Date.now() - stepStart\n          }\n        });\n\n        const result = await this.executeTool(toolUse.name, toolUse.input);\n\n        this.log({\n          type: \"tool_result\",\n          content: {\n            toolName: toolUse.name,\n            toolOutput: typeof result === \"string\" ? result.slice(0, 200) : JSON.stringify(result).slice(0, 200)\n          }\n        });\n\n        toolResults.push({\n          type: \"tool_result\",\n          tool_use_id: toolUse.id,\n          content: typeof result === \"string\" ? result : JSON.stringify(result)\n        });\n      }\n\n      messages.push({ role: \"user\", content: toolResults });\n    }\n\n    this.trace.endTime = Date.now();\n    this.trace.totalCost = this.calculateCost();\n    return this.trace;\n  }\n\n  private calculateCost(): number {\n    const inputCost = (this.trace.totalTokens.input / 1_000_000) * 3; // Sonnet pricing\n    const outputCost = (this.trace.totalTokens.output / 1_000_000) * 15;\n    return inputCost + outputCost;\n  }\n\n  private async executeTool(name: string, input: unknown): Promise<unknown> {\n    // Your tool execution logic here\n    return \"tool result\";\n  }\n\n  // Pretty-print the trace for debugging\n  printTrace() {\n    console.log(`\\n=== Agent Trace: ${this.trace.traceId} ===`);\n    console.log(`Task: ${this.trace.taskDescription}`);\n    console.log(`Outcome: ${this.trace.outcome}`);\n    console.log(`Duration: ${(this.trace.endTime! - this.trace.startTime) / 1000}s`);\n    console.log(`Tokens: ${this.trace.totalTokens.input} in / ${this.trace.totalTokens.output} out`);\n    console.log(`Cost: $${this.trace.totalCost.toFixed(4)}`);\n    console.log(`Steps: ${this.trace.steps.length}`);\n    console.log(\"\\nTimeline:\");\n    for (const step of this.trace.steps) {\n      const icon = { thinking: \"\\u{1F4AD}\", tool_call: \"\\u{1F527}\", tool_result: \"\\u{1F4CB}\", decision: \"\\u{1F500}\", error: \"\\u274C\" }[step.type];\n      console.log(`  ${icon} [${step.type}] ${step.content.toolName || step.content.reasoning?.slice(0, 80) || step.content.error || \"\"}`);\n    }\n  }\n}', language: 'typescript' },
              { type: 'tip', content: 'In production, ship traces to a structured logging system (like Loki or Elasticsearch) indexed by traceId. When a user reports a bad agent response, you can pull up the full execution trace and see exactly which step went wrong — was it bad reasoning, a failed tool call, or wrong context?' },
              { type: 'text', content: '### Debugging Common Agent Issues\n\n**Agent loops forever:**\nCheck trace for repeated tool calls with same params. Usually means the Observe step isn\'t detecting that nothing changed. Fix: add a \"seen states\" set and break if the same state repeats.\n\n**Agent takes wrong action:**\nLook at the thinking step before the bad tool call. Usually the reasoning was correct but the tool choice was wrong. Fix: improve tool descriptions or add a \"plan validation\" step.\n\n**Agent is slow:**\nCheck latency per tool call. Usually one specific tool (database query, API call) is the bottleneck. Fix: add caching, parallelize independent tool calls, or use a faster tool implementation.\n\n**Agent costs too much:**\nCheck token usage per step. Usually the system prompt + accumulated history grows large. Fix: summarize history, use a sliding window, or switch to a cheaper model for simple steps.\n\n**Agent gives wrong final answer:**\nTrace backwards from the final output. Find the last correct step and the first wrong step. The bug is in the transition between them.' }
            ],
            quiz: [
              { id: 'q1', question: 'Why is traditional debugging (breakpoints) insufficient for AI agents?', options: ['Agents are too fast to debug', 'Agents are non-deterministic — the same input can produce different execution paths', 'Agents can\'t be paused', 'Breakpoints slow down the model'], correctIndex: 1, explanation: 'AI agents are non-deterministic. The same task might take 5 steps one time and 12 steps the next, using different tools in different order. You need tracing (recording the full execution) rather than breakpoints (pausing at fixed locations).' },
              { id: 'q2', question: 'What is the most useful data to capture in an agent trace?', options: ['Only the final output', 'Only errors', 'Full message history, tool calls with params and results, token usage, and latency per step', 'Just the system prompt'], correctIndex: 2, explanation: 'A complete trace captures the full decision-making process: what the agent was thinking, what tools it called (with inputs/outputs), how many tokens were used, and how long each step took. This lets you replay and debug any issue.' }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ];
  }
}
